{"title_page": "Winchester Law School", "text_new": "[[File:HenrySTucker.jpg|thumb|Henry St. George Tucker, Sr., founder and operator of the Winchester Law School.]]\n\n'''Winchester Law School''' was a privately run institution for legal education.  Operated by [[Henry St. George Tucker, Sr.]], it was open from 1824 to 1831.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Commentaries on the Laws of Virginia.jpg|thumb|Title page of Volume 1 of Henry St. George Tucker's \"Commentaries on the Laws of Virginia\".  This work includes lectures he delivered while operating the Winchester Law School.]]\nIn 1824 Henry Tucker was named [[Chancellor#Functions related to justice and the law|Chancellor]] of the [[Court of equity|Equity Court]] of the Fourth District, with jurisdiction in [[Clarksburg, West Virginia|Clarksburg]] and [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]].  Since he had left the [[Virginia State Senate]] and a lucrative law practice to accept the judicial appointment, he needed to generate additional income.  Because he had previously worked as a law professor, Tucker decided to start a law school using a building at what is now 37 South Cameron Streer in Winchester.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=xnSPAAAAMAAJ&q=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&dq=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GJ6MUImZDuLo0gGGtIBw&ved=0CFQQ6AEwBzgK Legal Education in Virginia, 1779-1979], 1982, page 39</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://handley.pastperfectonline.com/photo/8BA8CCCB-4B44-4D00-96B5-673268167545 |title=37 S. Cameron St. |website=Stewart Bell Jr. Archives |publisher= Handley Regional Library |location=Winchester, VA |access-date=January 30, 2016 |quote=Location of Winchester Law School 1824 - 1831. Photo appears in \"A Factual History of Education in Winchester Virginia\" by Brant R. Harper, 1944.}}</ref>\n\nUsing his father [[St. George Tucker|St. George Tucker's]] copies of [[Commentaries on the Laws of England|Blackstone's Commentaries]] as the basis for his instruction, Henry Tucker lectured three days each week and gave his students regular quizzes to test their knowledge.  In addition, he prepared, edited and published ''Tucker's Notes on Blackstone's Commentaries for the Use of Students''.  ''Tucker's Commentaries'' provided the current state and federal law on each point covered by Blackstone, and was widely used because it focused on United States common law rather than English legal and political theory.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=UwQNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA345&dq=winchester+%22law+school%22+henry+st.+george+tucker&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PZKMUNCdBcqp0AG__IEY&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=winchester%20%22law%20school%22%20henry%20st.%20george%20tucker&f=false Virginia Law Books: Essays and Bibliographies], Volume 239, 2000, pages 345 to 347</ref>\n\nThe Winchester Law School was a success, largely because of Tucker's favorable reputation as an attorney and law professor.  He had 11 students in the 1824 to 1825 session, and the student body steadily increased until he had over 30 students each term.<ref>Steve Sheppard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=XQgrjw9qiqcC&pg=PA413&dq=winchester+%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QJ2MUIjAL4vU0gG704C4Cg&ved=0CF0Q6AEwCDgK#v=onepage&q=winchester%20%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22&f=false The History of Legal Education in the United States], Volume 1, 2007, page 413</ref><ref>Virginia State Bar Association, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DQjxAAAAIAAJ&q=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&dq=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GJ6MUImZDuLo0gGGtIBw&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCDgK Proceedings of the Annual Meeting of the Virginia State Bar Association], Volume 50, 1939, page 169</ref><ref>Samuel C. Mitchell, Editor, [https://books.google.com/books?id=L2yi-_uv0kgC&pg=PA338&dq=%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22+law+school+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KJ-MUP7NI8mE0QHy1IDgDw&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22%20law%20school%201824&f=false The South in the Building of the Nation], 2002, page 338</ref>\n\n==Closing==\nIn 1831 Tucker was elected to the Virginia Court of Appeals.  This position required him to relocate to [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] and necessitated the closing of the Winchester Law School.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=bHVZsaHcu58C&pg=PA43&dq=%22law+school%22+%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kZyMULLyLueT0QGRpoCwBA&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22law%20school%22%20%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22&f=false Essays on Legal Education in Nineteenth Century Virginia], 1998, page 43</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[John White Brockenbrough]], federal judge and founder of the [[Washington and Lee University School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John White Brockenbrough|url=http://law.wlu.edu/faculty/profiledetail.asp?id=354|publisher=Washington and Lee University School of Law|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[William B. Campbell]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] and [[Governor of Tennessee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William B. Campbell|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C000104|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[John R. Chambliss, Sr.]], wealthy [[Virginia]] [[Attorney at law (United States)|attorney]], [[Planter (American South)|planter]] and member of the [[Confederate States|Confederate Congress]]<ref>Ezra J. Warner, Jr., W. Buck Yearns, [https://books.google.com/books?id=k6VyjF_ZTukC&pg=PA45&dq=john+chambliss+winchester+law+school&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JhbdUJ-PE4eA9QS6wYGQAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=john%20chambliss%20winchester%20law%20school&f=false Biographical Register of the Confederate Congress], 1975, page 45</ref>\n*[[Robert M. T. Hunter]], [[List of Speakers of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], [[United States Senator]] from Virginia and [[Confederate States Secretary of State]]<ref>Martha T. Hunter, L. Quinton Washington, [https://books.google.com/books?id=vLdEAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA35&dq=%22Robert+M.+T.+Hunter%22+winchester+law+school&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mBbdUIG7IITe8ATewICAAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Robert%20M.%20T.%20Hunter%22%20winchester%20law%20school&f=false A Memoir of Robert M.T. Hunter], 1903, page 35</ref>\n*[[William L. Goggin]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William L. Goggin|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000256|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Zaccheus Collins Lee]], attorney and judge in [[Maryland]]<ref>Lee Family Digital Archive, Washington and Lee University, [http://blog.leearchive.org/2011/04/z-collins-lee-attends-edgar-allan-poes.html Z. Collins Lee Attends Edgar Allan Poe's Funeral], April 17, 2011</ref>\n*[[Isaac S. Pennybacker]], [[United States Senator]] from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Isaac S. Pennybacker|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1867&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Henry A. Wise]], [[Governor of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry A. Wise|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000649|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:1823 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:1831 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Independent law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education in Frederick County, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:HenrySTucker.jpg|thumb|Henry St. George Tucker, Sr., founder and operator of the Winchester Law School.]]\n\n'''Winchester Law School''' was a privately run institution for legal education.  Operated by [[Henry St. George Tucker, Sr.]], it was open from 1824 to 1831.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Commentaries on the Laws of Virginia.jpg|thumb|Title page of Volume 1 of Henry St. George Tucker's \"Commentaries on the Laws of Virginia\".  This work includes lectures he delivered while operating the Winchester Law School.]]\nIn 1824 Henry Tucker was named [[Chancellor#Functions related to justice and the law|Chancellor]] of the [[Court of equity|Equity Court]] of the Fourth District, with jurisdiction in [[Clarksburg, West Virginia|Clarksburg]] and [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]].  Since he had left the [[Virginia State Senate]] and a lucrative law practice to accept the judicial appointment, he needed to generate additional income.  Because he had previously worked as a law professor, Tucker decided to start a law school using a building at what is now 37 South Cameron Streer in Winchester.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=xnSPAAAAMAAJ&q=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&dq=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GJ6MUImZDuLo0gGGtIBw&ved=0CFQQ6AEwBzgK Legal Education in Virginia, 1779-1979], 1982, page 39</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://handley.pastperfectonline.com/photo/8BA8CCCB-4B44-4D00-96B5-673268167545 |title=37 S. Cameron St. |website=Stewart Bell Jr. Archives |publisher= Handley Regional Library |location=Winchester, VA |access-date=January 30, 2016 |quote=Location of Winchester Law School 1824 - 1831. Photo appears in \"A Factual History of Education in Winchester Virginia\" by Brant R. Harper, 1944.}}</ref>\n\nUsing his father [[St. George Tucker|St. George Tucker's]] copies of [[Commentaries on the Laws of England|Blackstone's Commentaries]] as the basis for his instruction, Henry Tucker lectured three days each week and gave his students regular quizzes to test their knowledge.  In addition, he prepared, edited and published ''Tucker's Notes on Blackstone's Commentaries for the Use of Students''.  ''Tucker's Commentaries'' provided the current state and federal law on each point covered by Blackstone, and was widely used because it focused on United States common law rather than English legal and political theory.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=UwQNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA345&dq=winchester+%22law+school%22+henry+st.+george+tucker&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PZKMUNCdBcqp0AG__IEY&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=winchester%20%22law%20school%22%20henry%20st.%20george%20tucker&f=false Virginia Law Books: Essays and Bibliographies], Volume 239, 2000, pages 345 to 347</ref>\n\nThe Winchester Law School was a success, largely because of Tucker's favorable reputation as an attorney and law professor.  He had 11 students in the 1824 to 1825 session, and the student body steadily increased until he had over 30 students each term.<ref>Steve Sheppard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=XQgrjw9qiqcC&pg=PA413&dq=winchester+%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QJ2MUIjAL4vU0gG704C4Cg&ved=0CF0Q6AEwCDgK#v=onepage&q=winchester%20%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22&f=false The History of Legal Education in the United States], Volume 1, 2007, page 413</ref><ref>Virginia State Bar Association, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DQjxAAAAIAAJ&q=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&dq=%22winchester+law+school%22+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GJ6MUImZDuLo0gGGtIBw&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCDgK Proceedings of the Annual Meeting of the Virginia State Bar Association], Volume 50, 1939, page 169</ref><ref>Samuel C. Mitchell, Editor, [https://books.google.com/books?id=L2yi-_uv0kgC&pg=PA338&dq=%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22+law+school+1824&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KJ-MUP7NI8mE0QHy1IDgDw&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22%20law%20school%201824&f=false The South in the Building of the Nation], 2002, page 338</ref>\n\n==Closing==\nIn 1831 Tucker was elected to the Virginia Court of Appeals.  This position required him to relocate to [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] and necessitated the closing of the Winchester Law School.<ref>William Hamilton Bryson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=bHVZsaHcu58C&pg=PA43&dq=%22law+school%22+%22henry+st.+george+tucker%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kZyMULLyLueT0QGRpoCwBA&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22law%20school%22%20%22henry%20st.%20george%20tucker%22&f=false Essays on Legal Education in Nineteenth Century Virginia], 1998, page 43</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[John White Brockenbrough]], federal judge and founder of the [[Washington and Lee University School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John White Brockenbrough|url=http://law.wlu.edu/faculty/profiledetail.asp?id=354|publisher=Washington and Lee University School of Law|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[William B. Campbell]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] and [[Governor of Tennessee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William B. Campbell|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C000104|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[John R. Chambliss, Sr.]], wealthy [[Virginia]] [[Attorney at law (United States)|attorney]], [[Planter (American South)|planter]] and member of the [[Confederate States|Confederate Congress]]<ref>Ezra J. Warner, Jr., W. Buck Yearns, [https://books.google.com/books?id=k6VyjF_ZTukC&pg=PA45&dq=john+chambliss+winchester+law+school&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JhbdUJ-PE4eA9QS6wYGQAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=john%20chambliss%20winchester%20law%20school&f=false Biographical Register of the Confederate Congress], 1975, page 45</ref>\n*[[Robert M. T. Hunter]], [[List of Speakers of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], [[United States Senator]] from Virginia and [[Confederate States Secretary of State]]<ref>Martha T. Hunter, L. Quinton Washington, [https://books.google.com/books?id=vLdEAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA35&dq=%22Robert+M.+T.+Hunter%22+winchester+law+school&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mBbdUIG7IITe8ATewICAAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Robert%20M.%20T.%20Hunter%22%20winchester%20law%20school&f=false A Memoir of Robert M.T. Hunter], 1903, page 35</ref>\n*[[William L. Goggin]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William L. Goggin|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000256|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Zaccheus Collins Lee]], attorney and judge in [[Maryland]]<ref>Lee Family Digital Archive, Washington and Lee University, [http://blog.leearchive.org/2011/04/z-collins-lee-attends-edgar-allan-poes.html Z. Collins Lee Attends Edgar Allan Poe's Funeral], April 17, 2011</ref>\n*[[Isaac S. Pennybacker]], [[United States Senator]] from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Isaac S. Pennybacker|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1867&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Henry A. Wise]], [[Governor of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry A. Wise|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000649|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:1823 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:1831 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Independent law schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education in Frederick County, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winchester_Law_School"}
{"title_page": "1st Grey Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox Canadian football game\n| number         = 1\n| type           = Grey Cup\n| image          =\n| date           = December 4, 1909\n| stadium        = [[Rosedale Field]]\n| city           = [[Rosedale, Toronto]]\n| visitor name   = [[Toronto Varsity Blues]]\n| visitor colour = Toronto Varsity Blues\n| home name      = [[Toronto Parkdale]]\n| home colour    = \n| visitor coach  = [[Harry Griffith (coach)|Harry Griffith]]\n| home coach     = [[Eddie Livingstone]]\n| visitor record = 6\u20130\n| home record    = 3\u20131\n| visitor1       = 6\n| visitor2       = 0\n| visitor3       = 10\n| visitor4       = 10\n| home1          = 0\n| home2          = 5\n| home3          = 1\n| home4          = 0\n| referee        = W.B. Hendry\n| attendance     = 3,807\n| previous       = [[1908 Dominion Championship|1908 Championship]]\n}}\nThe '''1st [[Grey Cup]]''' game was played on December 4, 1909, between the [[CIS football|Intercollegiate Rugby Football Union]] champion [[Toronto Varsity Blues football|University of Toronto Varsity Blues]] and the [[Ontario Rugby Football Union]] champion [[Toronto Parkdale Canoe Club]]. The University of Toronto won the game, 26-6.<ref>{{cite web|title=CFL Guide and Record Book, 2017 Edition |url=https://d3ham790trbkqy.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/CFL-Book-2017-Perfect-Bind.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto off form (page 5 of archive)|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=pusiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=In8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6737%2C3445615|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|date=December 3, 1906|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> While the [[Canadian Dominion Football Championship]] had been contested since 1884, this was the first such game that was awarded a trophy.<ref name=\"CFHOF\">{{citation |url=http://cfhof.ca/history-of-the-grey-cup/ |title=History of the Grey Cup |publisher=Canadian Football Hall of Fame and Museum |accessdate=2012-06-27}}</ref> This was the University of Toronto's third Dominion Championship and their fifth appearance in the national championship game. This was Toronto Parkdale's first appearance in a Dominion Championship game.\n\n[[File:1909 Grey Cup Champions.jpg|thumb|left|The 1909 Varsity Blues, inaugural champions.  The Grey Cup is pictured at the front right.]]\n\n==Game summary==\n'''U. of Toronto Varsity Blues''' (26) - TDs, [[Hugh Gall]], [[Murray Thomson (football player)|Murray Thomson]], [[Smirle Lawson]]; cons., [[Bill Ritchie (football player)|Bill Ritchie]]; singles, [[Hugh Gall|Gall]] (8), [[Smirle Lawson|Lawson]] (2).\n\n'''Toronto Parkdale Canoe Club''' (6) - TD, [[Tom Meighan (football player)|Tom Meighan]]; single, [[Percy Killaly]].\n\n==See also==\n* {{cite web |url=http://greycup.cfl.ca/1909gc |title=Grey Cup 1909 |publisher=Canadian Football League |accessdate=14 December 2008  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207082200/http://greycup.cfl.ca/1909gc |archivedate=2008-12-07 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/uploads/assets/CFL/PDF_Docs/2009_GreyCup_Records.pdf |title=The Grey Cup 1909-2009 |publisher=Canadian Football League |accessdate=28 December 2010  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202142551/http://www.cfl.ca/uploads/assets/CFL/PDF_Docs/2009_GreyCup_Records.pdf |archivedate=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Toronto Varsity Blues football navbox}}\n{{Grey Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grey Cup}}\n[[Category:Grey Cup|01]]\n[[Category:1909 in Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Grey Cups hosted in Toronto]]\n[[Category:December 1909 sports events]]\n[[Category:1900s in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Toronto Varsity Blues football]]\n\n\n{{Canadianfootball-competition-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Canadian football game\n| number         = 1\n| type           = Grey Cup\n| image          =\n| date           = December 4, 1909\n| stadium        = [[Rosedale Field]]\n| city           = [[Rosedale, Toronto]]\n| visitor name   = [[Toronto Varsity Blues]]\n| visitor colour = Toronto Varsity Blues\n| home name      = [[Toronto Parkdale]]\n| home colour    = \n| visitor coach  = [[Harry Griffith (coach)|Harry Griffith]]\n| home coach     = [[Eddie Livingstone]]\n| visitor record = 6\u20130\n| home record    = 3\u20131\n| visitor1       = 6\n| visitor2       = 0\n| visitor3       = 10\n| visitor4       = 10\n| home1          = 0\n| home2          = 5\n| home3          = 1\n| home4          = 0\n| referee        = W.B. Hendry\n| attendance     = 3,807\n| previous       = [[1908 Dominion Championship|1908 Championship]]\n}}\nThe '''1st [[Grey Cup]]''' game was played on December 4, 1909, between the [[CIS football|Intercollegiate Rugby Football Union]] champion [[Toronto Varsity Blues football|University of Toronto Varsity Blues]] and the [[Ontario Rugby Football Union]] champion [[Toronto Parkdale Canoe Club]]. The University of Toronto won the game, 26-6.<ref>{{cite web|title=CFL Guide and Record Book, 2017 Edition |url=https://d3ham790trbkqy.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/CFL-Book-2017-Perfect-Bind.pdf|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto off form (page 5 of archive)|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=pusiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=In8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6737%2C3445615|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|date=December 3, 1906|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> While the [[Canadian Dominion Football Championship]] had been contested since 1884, this was the first such game that was awarded a trophy.<ref name=\"CFHOF\">{{citation |url=http://cfhof.ca/history-of-the-grey-cup/ |title=History of the Grey Cup |publisher=Canadian Football Hall of Fame and Museum |accessdate=2012-06-27}}</ref> This was the University of Toronto's third Dominion Championship and their fifth appearance in the national championship game. This was Toronto Parkdale's first appearance in a Dominion Championship game.\n\n[[File:1909 Grey Cup Champions.jpg|thumb|left|The 1909 Varsity Blues, inaugural champions.  The Grey Cup is pictured at the front right.]]\n\n==Game summary==\n'''U. of Toronto Varsity Blues''' (26) - TDs, [[Hugh Gall]], [[Murray Thomson (football player)|Murray Thomson]], [[Smirle Lawson]]; cons., [[Bill Ritchie (football player)|Bill Ritchie]]; singles, [[Hugh Gall|Gall]] (8), [[Smirle Lawson|Lawson]] (2).\n\n'''Toronto Parkdale Canoe Club''' (6) - TD, [[Tom Meighan (football player)|Tom Meighan]]; single, [[Percy Killaly]].\n\n==See also==\n* {{cite web |url=http://greycup.cfl.ca/1909gc |title=Grey Cup 1909 |publisher=Canadian Football League |accessdate=14 December 2008  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207082200/http://greycup.cfl.ca/1909gc |archivedate=2008-12-07 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/uploads/assets/CFL/PDF_Docs/2009_GreyCup_Records.pdf |title=The Grey Cup 1909-2009 |publisher=Canadian Football League |accessdate=28 December 2010  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101202142551/http://www.cfl.ca/uploads/assets/CFL/PDF_Docs/2009_GreyCup_Records.pdf |archivedate=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Toronto Varsity Blues football navbox}}\n{{Grey Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grey Cup}}\n[[Category:Grey Cup|01]]\n[[Category:1909 in Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Grey Cups hosted in Toronto]]\n[[Category:1909 in Ontario]]\n[[Category:December 1909 sports events]]\n[[Category:20th century in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Toronto Varsity Blues football]]\n\n\n{{Canadianfootball-competition-stub}}\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Grey_Cup"}
{"title_page": "William S. Richardson School of Law", "text_new": "{{Infobox law school \n| name     = William S. Richardson<br/>School of Law\n| image =  [[File:William S. Richardson School of Law.png|180px]]\n|established  = 1973\n|parent = [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]]\n|type              = Public\n|endowment =\n|parent endowment =\n|head              = [[Aviam Soifer]] \n|students          = 257\n|faculty = 52\n|ranking = 91\n|annual tuition =\n|city              = Honolulu\n|state = HI\n|country = United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|21|17|47|N|157|49|05|W|region:US-HI_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| homepage      =  http://www.law.hawaii.edu/\n| motto             = {{lang|haw|Ma luna a{{okina}}e o na lahui a pau ke ola ke kanaka}} ([[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]])<br />''Above all nations is humanity''\n| aba profile = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=62 William S. Richardson School of Law Profile]\n| logo               = [[File:Richardson Logo.jpg]]\n}}\n\nThe [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] '''William S. Richardson School of Law''' is a public law school located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]] in [[Honolulu]]. Named after its patriarch, former [[Hawaii State Supreme Court]] [[Chief Justice]] [[William S. Richardson]], a zealous advocate of Hawaiian culture,<ref name=\"Hevesi\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/us/25richardson.html?ref=dennis_hevesi|title=William S. Richardson, Ex-Chief Justice in Hawaii, Dies at 90|last=Hevesi|first=Dennis|date=2010-06-28|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> it is the state's only law school.<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutlawschools.org/lawschool/william-s-richardson-school-of-law|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa (William S. Richardson School of Law)|last=|first=|date=|work=University of Hawaii at Manoa (William S. Richardson School of Law)|publisher=About Law Schools|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309222222/http://www.aboutlawschools.org/lawschool/william-s-richardson-school-of-law/|archive-date=August 9, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRichardson's regime of legal studies places special emphasis on fields of law of particular importance to Hawaii and the surrounding [[Pacific Rim|Pacific]] and [[Asia]]n region, including [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Native Hawaiian Law Certificate|Native Hawaiian Law]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate|Pacific-Asian Legal Studies]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Environmental Law Certificate|Environmental Law]], and [[maritime law]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Aug/24/op/hawaii808240327.html|title=Concern For Others Key To Law School's Mission|last=Mariani-Belding|first=Jeanne|date=August 4, 2008|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202033948/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Aug/24/op/hawaii808240327.html|archive-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA member of the [[Association of american law schools|Association of American Law Schools]] (AALS), the school is accredited by the Council of the Section of Legal Education and Admissions to the Bar of the [[American Bar Association]] (ABA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2011/11/10/university-of-hawaii-law-school.html|title=University of Hawaii Law School Retains ABA Accreditation|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2011|newspaper=Pacific Business News|accessdate=February 19, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010019/http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2011/11/10/university-of-hawaii-law-school.html|archive-date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> It offers a [[Juris Doctor]], with certificates available in [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Native Hawaiian Law Certificate|Native Hawaiian Law]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate|Pacific-Asian Legal Studies]], and [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Environmental Law Certificate|Environmental Law]], with students able to matriculate either full-time or part-time. It also offers an Advanced Juris Doctor, for foreign students who have earned a law degree abroad, and a [[LLM]].\n\nFor 2016, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked Richardson as 82nd among the nations law schools.<ref name=\"Above The Law\">{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/03/the-2016-u-s-news-law-school-rankings-are-here/2/|title=The 2016 U.S. News Law School Rankings Are Here!|last1=Zaretsky|first1=Staci|date=March 10, 2015|website=Above The Law|publisher=Above The Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909193346/http://abovethelaw.com:80/2015/03/the-2016-u-s-news-law-school-rankings-are-here/2/|archive-date=September 9, 2017|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>  Richardson's part-time program was ranked 30th.<ref name=\"U.S. News and World Report\">{{cite news|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa -Richardson|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-hawaii-manoa-richardson-03043|accessdate=3 September 2014|publisher=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref>\n\n==William S. Richardson==\n{{Main|William S. Richardson}}\n\nThe establishment of the Law School in 1973, was considered the achievement of former [[Hawaii State Supreme Court]] [[Chief Justice]], [[William S. Richardson]].<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\" /> For many years he had pressed the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] for its creation, arguing that the state would benefit by providing a legal education for its residents that enveloped its cultural customs\u2014because they had the greatest stake in constructing the state's legal traditions going forward as such. At his retirement, the Law School was named in his honor.\n\n==Ethos==\n{{Main|K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe}}\n[[File:Plaque Kanawai Mamalahoe.jpg|300px|thumb|K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe, on a plaque under the [[Kamehameha Statues]].]]\nThe spirit of Richardson's culture as a community devoted to the study of law is manifested in [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], the fundamental precept of Hawaiian law.\n\nOriginating in a royal edict by [[Kamehameha I|King Kamehameha]] I in 1797, galvanizing the [[Kingdom of Hawai'i]]'s legal system, [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], or Law of the Splintered Paddle, was enshrined later in the [[Constitution of Hawaii|Hawaii State Constitution]], Article 9, Section 10.<ref name=\"hawaii1\">[[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]] holds that government should strive for justice and to protect the rights of all of humanity through the rule of law. [http://www.hawaii.edu/uhelp/files/LawOfTheSplinteredPaddle.pdf The Law of the Splintered Paddle: K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]. (PDF). hawaii.edu</ref>\n\nAccording to Hawaiian legend, [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]] was declared by King Kamehameha after an incident where he chased two fishermen who were fishing illegally, when he caught his leg in the reef, and one of the fisherman, Kaleleiki, hit him mightily on the head with a paddle in defense, which broke into pieces. Luckily, Kamehameha was able to escape. Years later, Kamehameha held, when the same fisherman was brought before him to account for the incident, that in the interest of justice he should be released, as he had only been searching for food for his family.<ref name=\"hawaii1\"/>\n\nReflecting [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], the school maintains a \"commitment... to a collaborative community that is deeply committed to the... pursuit of social and economic justice\" for all.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|title=About William S. Richardson School of Law Mission Statement|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/about-us|work=About William S. Richardson School of Law Mission Statement|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> Reflecting this commitment, its unofficial logo is Kaleleiki, the fisherman.\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:William S. Richardson School of Law, Street View.jpg|220x220px|thumb|University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa Campus With The William S. Richardson School of Law Library In Background]]\n*1968 \u2013 The [[Hawaii State Legislature]] established the William S. Richardson School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|title= William S. Richardson Timeline|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/time-line|work=Timeline|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n*1973 \u2013 Richardson welcomed its first class, including 53 students.\n*1972 \u2013 David Hood appointed Dean.\n*1974 \u2013 The [[American Bar Association]] granted William S. Richardson School of Law provisional accreditation.\n*1976 \u2013 Jerome Dupont appointed Acting Dean.\n*1977 \u2013 Cliff Thompson appointed Dean.\n*1978 \u2013 Richardson holds first [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Law school traditions|Ete Bowl]].\n*1979 \u2013 ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' created.\n\n===1980s===\n*1981 \u2013 Richard Miller appointed Dean.\n*1982 \u2013 The [[American Bar Association]] granted William S. Richardson School of Law full accreditation.\n*1982 \u2013 Richardson sends first [[Moot Court]] Team to competition.\n*1983 \u2013 William S. Richardson School of Law moved into new facilities on the campus of the [[University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa]].\n*1983 \u2013 Richardson Law Library opens.\n*1983 \u2013 Pacific-Asian Legal Studies program begins.\n*1985 \u2013 Jeremy Harrison appointed Dean.\n*1985 \u2013 [[Student Bar Association]] Formed.\n*1987 \u2013 Theschool joins [[United States Supreme Court]] Jurists-In-Residence Program\n\n===1990s===\n\n*1991 \u2013 Elder Law Program formed.\n*1992 \u2013 Environmental Law Certificate established.\n*1995 \u2013 Lawrence Foster appointed Dean.\n*1995 \u2013 Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate established.\n\n===2000s===\n\n*2002 \u2013 Law Student Pledge adopted.\n*2003 \u2013 [[Aviam Soifer]] appointed dean.<ref>{{cite news|last=Espanol|first=Zenaida Serrano|title=Nominee for UH law dean approved|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2003/Mar/15/ln/ln14a.html|accessdate=2011-09-27|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|date=2003-03-15}}</ref>\n*2003 \u2013 [[William S. Richardson School of Law#LLM Degree|LLM]] program started.<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2003/02/10/news/index8.html|title=UH To Begin Law For Foreign-Trained Lawyers|last=|first=|date=February 10, 2003|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n*2005 \u2013 [[Native Hawaiians#Ka Huli Ao: Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law|Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law]] established<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/kahuliao|title=Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law {{!}} William S. Richardson School of Law|website=www.law.hawaii.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> through a ''[[Native Hawaiians#Native American Programs Act|Native Hawaiian Education Act]]'' grant.\n*2005 \u2013 Hawaii Innocence Project established.\n*2008 \u2013 Richardson established a part-time evening law program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Dec/10/br/br8465319720.html|title=UH Law School to launch part-time programs|last=|first=|date=December 10, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=September 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404215849/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Dec/10/br/br8465319720.html|archive-date=April 2, 2017}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 Richardson received a grant from [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS Media Holdings]] in [[Seoul, South Korea]] for $200,000 to establish a Korean Law Faculty Fund.<ref name=\"lawfund\">{{cite news|title=University of Hawaii Creates Korean Law Fund|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2009/02/16/daily23.html|accessdate=2012-02-19|newspaper=Pacific Business News|date=2009-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n\n*2010 \u2013 Chief Justice [[William S. Richardson]] died on June 21.<ref name=\"Hevesi\"/>\n*2011 \u2013 Professor Jon Van Dyke died.\n*2016 \u2013 Dean Jeremy Thomas Harrison died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legalnews.com/detroit/1424717|title=Former MSU Law dean dies, 80 > Detroit Legal News|last=|first=|date=May 13, 2016|website=www.legalnews.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n\n===2016===\n* ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked Richardson 82nd amongst its 142 ranked law  schools.<ref name=\"Above The Law\"/> Richardson's part-time program was ranked 30th.<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite web|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa \u2013 Richardson|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-hawaii-manoa-richardson-03043|website=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Richardson's official 2013 ABA-required disclosures, 50.9% of the Class of 2013 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/sites/www.law.hawaii.edu/files/content/ABA%20Employment%20Summary%20Class%202013.pdf|title=Employment Statistics|last=American Bar Association|first=|date=April 9, 2014|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> Richardson's [[Law School Transparency]] under-employment score is 10.2%, indicating the percentage of the class of 2017 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a short-term, part-time, or non-professional job nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/hawaii/2013/|title=University of Hawaii Law School Transparency Report|last=|first=|date=|website=Law School Transparency|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> It is unclear whether the Law School's above-average clerkship placement rate for new graduates is reflected in these numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2012/04/03|title=New Study Ranks Richardson Law School High in Top 20 Law Schools That Help Graduates Find State and Local Clerkships|last=|first=|date=April 12, 2012|website=Richardson School of Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826221706/https://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2012/04/03|archive-date=August 6, 2016|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at the Richardson School of Law for the 2014\u20132015 academic year is $37,934 for Hawaii residents and $57,662 for non-residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/cost-attendance|title=Cost of Attendance}}</ref> Law School Transparency has estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years is $166,060 for residents and $261,639 for non-residents in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/hawaii/costs/2013/|title=University of Hawaii Total Debt|last=|first=|date=|website=Law School Transparency|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>  In July 2016, Richardson was ranked #1 by U.S. News & World Report among American law schools whose alumni have the least debt, at an average of $54,988 for the Class of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/the-short-list-grad-school/articles/2016-07-19/10-law-schools-where-alumni-have-the-least-debt|title=10 Law Schools Where Alumni Have the Least Debt|last=Smith-Barrow|first=Delece|date=July 19, 2016|website=U.S. News and World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116073122/http://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/the-short-list-grad-school/articles/2016-07-19/10-law-schools-where-alumni-have-the-least-debt|archive-date=January 16, 2017|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Richardson Law Library Entrance 2012-04-20.png|300x300px|right|frame|The William S. Richardson School of Law Library]]\n\n==Institutes, programs & centers==\n\n=== Institutes ===\n*Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law. The Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law was established in June 2006. Its goal is to become an academic center for research and training in the  field of business law in Asia and the Pacific.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/iapbl|title=Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law|last=|first=|date=|work=Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> The Institute focuses on commercial law, insolvency and secured transactions, corporate law and business transactions, securities, intellectual property, real estate financing, and labor law issues. The Institute's activities facilitate direct exchanges between the academic, legal, and business communities in Hawaii and throughout the Asia-Pacific region.\n*Hammurabi Legal Forum: The Hammurabi Legal Forum for the Rule of Law (HLF) was established in 2008 at the school to aid law schools in Iraq re-invigorate the country's tradition of scholarship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2008/11/10/story6.html|title=UH Students Help Struggling Iraqi Law School|last=Chiem|first=Linda|date=November 9, 2008|newspaper=Pacific Business News|accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref> By providing an  online database of free legal resources, HLF originally sought to provide information on issues that are important to Iraq and the Iraqi legal community. In 2009, the HLF expanded its efforts to assist Rule of Law activities in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq. In 2010, it further expanded its research to incorporate additional regions of the globe, including Afghanistan and the Pacific Region, with a special focus on Timor-Leste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/malamalama/2011/03/pietsch/|title=University of Hawaii professor promotes rule of law in Iraq {{!}} Malamalama, The Magazine of the University of Hawai'i System|last=Char|first=Kymber-Lee|date=March 30, 2011|website=www.hawaii.edu|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Programs ===\n* Hawaii Innocence Project: The Hawaii Innocence Project's mission is to provide [[pro bono]] representation to incarcerated persons who have a credible claim of actual innocence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jan/31/br/br8617503492.html|title=UH Manoa Law School Programs Awarded $18,500|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204948/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jan/31/br/br8617503492.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jun/29/br/br3658941702.html|title=UH Law School's 'Innocence Project' Gets 10K Grant|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182711/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jun/29/br/br3658941702.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n:University of Hawaii Elder Law Program (UHELP): Operating throughout the year, UHELP provides Hawaii's elder community basic legal assistance, advice and information.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/03/ln/FP606030343.html|title=$3.2 Million Settlement Benefits Elders, UH|last=Creamer|first=Beverly|date=June 3, 2006|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182808/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/03/ln/FP606030343.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/uhelp/|title=UHELP Community Services|last=|first=|date=|work=UHELP Community Services|publisher=UHELP|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Centers ===\n*Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law. Established in 2005 through a Native Hawaiian Education Act grant, the Center is an academic center that promotes education, scholarship, community outreach and collaboration on issues of law, culture and justice for Native Hawaiians and other Pacific and Indigenous peoples.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Nov/07/br/br6174253890.html|title=Hawaii Law School Program Receives $630,000 Grant|last=|first=|date=November 7, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222113/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Nov/07/br/br6174253890.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> The center focuses on education, research and scholarship, community outreach, and the preservation of historical, legal, and traditional and customary materials. It also offers new courses and supports Native Hawaiian and other law students as they pursue legal careers and leadership roles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jun/26/ln/ln11p.html|title=UH Plans Native Hawaiian Law Center|last=Creamer|first=Beverly|date=June 26, 2005|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182609/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jun/26/ln/ln11p.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.news.blogs.civilbeat.com/post/49474039062/uhm-native-hawaiian-law-center-unveils-new-publication|title=UHM Native Hawaiian Law Center Unveils New Publication|last=|first=|date=May 2, 2013|website=Civil Beat|publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224103418/http://hawaii.news.blogs.civilbeat.com/post/49474039062/uhm-native-hawaiian-law-center-unveils-new-publication|archive-date=December 24, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref>\n*Hawaii Health Law Policy Center aims to 1) to conduct and disseminate research on health law policy aimed at improving health care access in Hawaii; 2) to serve as a focus for multidisciplinary research, teaching, on health law and policy in the context of Hawaii; and 3) to bring community leaders, health care policymakers, faculty members, and students together to find solutions to health care shortages and other barriers to access in Hawaii's rural, impoverished, or otherwise underserved communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/health-law-policy-center|title=Health Law Policy Center|last=|first=|date=|work=Health Law Policy Center|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Scholarly publications==\n\n=== ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' ===\nThe ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' is a scholarly legal journal run by students that publishes works by jurists, scholars and practitioners. It publishes two issues annually, and hosts a biennial symposium.\n\n=== ''Asian-Pacific Law & Policy Journal'' ===\nThe ''Asian-Pacific Law and Policy Journal''is a biannual [[peer-reviewed]] [[open-access]] [[law journal]] published by the school. It covers issues facing [[Asia]] and the [[Pacific Rim]]. The journal was established in February 2000, with Jim Hitchingham as [[editor-in-chief]] and with assistance and support from Lawrence Foster, Dean of the law school, and professors Ronald Brown and Mark Levin. In addition to its web format, the journal is available through the legal databases [[LexisNexis]] and [[Westlaw]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/law/pals/journal.html|title=ASIAN-PACIFIC LAW & POLICY JOURNAL (APLPJ)|last=|first=|date=|website=manoa.hawaii.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Visiting tribunals & jurist-in-residence programs==\n\n===Visiting tribunals===\n\n====United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit & Hawaii Supreme Court====\n\nEach year, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] sits specially at the school to hear some appeals from the [[United States District Court]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Hawaii|Districts of Hawaii]] and [[District Court of Guam|Guam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ninth Circuit Sitting In Honolulu Includes Visit To University of Hawaii|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2009/10/07|work=Press Release|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2013/09/30/9th-us-circuit-court-of-appeals-will.html|title=9th US Circuit Court of Appeals Will Hear Arguments in Honolulu|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Pacific Business News|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] also sits regularly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/115184184.html?id=115184184|title=Hawaii Supreme Court to hear case at UH law school|last=|first=|date=February 3, 2011|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courts.state.hi.us/news_and_reports/press_releases/2011/02/oral_argument_at_law_school.html|title=Hawaii Supreme Court to Hear Oral Argument at Law School|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Hawaii Judiciary|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Jurist-in-residence programs===\n\n====Bright International Jurist-in-Residence Program====\n\nStarted in 2007 under the tutelage of Senior Circuit Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit|United States Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit]], [[Myron Bright|Myron H Bright]], the Bright International Jurist-in-Residence program hosts international jurists to facilitate dialogue with the wider community and the school's faculty and staff.\n\nIn 2007, [[Israel Supreme Court]] judge [[Aharon Barak]] was the visiting scholar. In 2010, the president of the [[International Court of Justice]] [[Hisashi Owada]] served as visiting scholar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caselombardi.com/jurist.html|title=Jurist-In-residence program {{!}} Case Lombardi & Pettit|website=www.caselombardi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n====U.S. Supreme Court Jurist-in-Residence Program====\n\nInstituted in 1987, with the support of [[Myron H. Bright]], a Senior Circuit Judge for the [[United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit|United States Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit]], Richardson has a [[U.S. Supreme Court]] Jurist-In-Residence Program.  Biannually, a visiting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] Justice presents seminars on current judicial issues as well as teaches classes.<ref>{{cite web|title= US Supreme Court Jurist Residence program|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/us-supreme-court-jurist-residence-program}}</ref> \n[[File:Alito Civ Pro.jpg|300px|thumb|right|[[Samuel Alito|Supreme Court Justice Samuel Alito]] Teaching Richardson Civil Procedure Class, 2011]]\n\n==Faculty==\n\n=== Endowed professorship & faculty chairs ===\n\nThrough the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] Foundation, Richardson has been endowed with several professorships and faculty chairs.\n\n* Benjamin A. Kudo Professor of Law<ref>{{cite web|title=Chairs and Professorships|url=http://www.uhfoundation.org/gift_impact/faculty/chairs_professorships.aspx|work=Chairs and Professorships|publisher=University of Hawaii Foundation|accessdate=2012-02-19}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Inouye|Dan & Maggie Inouye]] Distinguished Chair In Democratic Ideas\n* [[Fred Korematsu|Fred T. Korematsu]] Professorship In Law and Social Justice<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uhfoundation.org/donor_resources/giving_opportunities/korematsu.aspx|title=The Fred T. Korematsu Chair In Law And Social Justice At The William S. Richardson School Of Law|last=|first=|date=April 13, 2012|newspaper=University of Hawaii Foundation|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n* George J Johnson Visiting Professor Endowment\n* Michael J. Marks Distinguished Professor of Business Law<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael J. Marks Distinguished Professorship in Business Law Established|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=4101|work=Michael J.  Marks Distinguished Professorship in Business Law Established|publisher=University of Hawaii|accessdate=2012-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/michael-j-marks-distinguished-professorship-in-business-law-established-at-uh-manoa/123|title=Michael J Marks Distinguished Professorship In Business Law Established At UH Manoa|last=|first=|date=December 20, 2010|newspaper=The Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n* Wallace S. Fujiyama Distinguished Visiting Professor of Law<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=4859|title=Law School January Term Brings Outstanding Scholars To Hawaii|publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n* Carlsmith Ball Faculty Scholar Fund<ref>{{cite news|title=Law Firm Endows Faculty Scholar Fund At UH|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2008/11/10/story6.html|accessdate=2012-02-19|newspaper=Pacific Business News|date=2008-07-30}}</ref>\n* [[SBS (Korea)|SBS Holdings Co]]. Korean Faculty Fund<ref name=\"lawfund\"/>\n\n=== Notable faculty ===\n\nIn 2013,''[[The Princeton Review]]'' ranked the Richardson faculty as the third \"Most Diverse Faculty.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/UniversityofHawaiiatManoaSchoolofLaw.aspx|title=William S. Richardson School of Law|last=|first=|date=March 12, 2013|newspaper=Princeton Review|accessdate=March 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010014250/http://www.princetonreview.com:80/schools/1035770/law/university-hawaii-at-manoa-william-s-richardson-school-law|archive-date=October 10, 2016}}</ref> And, in 2012, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked the school 3rd of 190 Law Schools for \"Smallest Faculty-Student Ratio\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/article/uh-law-school-named-best-minority-students-and-one-nations-top-169-princeton-review|title=UH Law School Named 'Best' For Minority Students|last=|first=|date=October 10, 2013|website=|publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa William S Richardson School of Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103083208/https://www.law.hawaii.edu/article/uh-law-school-named-best-minority-students-and-one-nations-top-169-princeton-review|archive-date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> The faculty is specialized in an array of legal areas.\n\n'''Current notable faculty''':\n* David L. Callies, Scholar of the Law of Real Property\n* Tae-Ung Baik, Former Korean Prisoner of Conscience,<ref>{{cite web|title=South Korea: Prisoner of Conscience Baik Tae-Ung|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA25/024/1993/en|work=South Korea: Prisoner of Conscience Baik Tae-Ung|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref> Specialist in International Human Rights Law and Korean Law\n* [[Mari Matsuda]], Activist legal scholar, lawyer, first tenured Female Asian-American law professor\n*[[Randall Roth (professor)|Randall Roth]]\n*[[Richard W. Pollack]]\n*[[Aviam Soifer]], Constitutional law scholar, former Dean of Boston College Law School\n*[[Eric Yamamoto]], Korematsu Professor of Law and Social Justice,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=5037|title=Law School Professor Eric Yamamoto Awarded Korematsu Professorship|last=|first=|date=April 17, 2012|publisher=University of Hawaii Manoa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161102152617/http://www.manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=5037|archive-date=November 2, 2016|accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Former faculty'''\n\n*[[Chris Iijima]], Legal scholar, Asian-American civil rights activist, folk singer (Deceased)\n*Jon Van Dyke, Constitutional law scholar, lawyer, activist (Deceased)<ref>{{cite news|last=Dayton|first=Kevin|title=UH Constitutional Law Professor Jon Van Dyke Dies|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/UH_constitutional_law_professor_Jon_Van_Dyke_dies.html?id=134764028|accessdate=2011-11-30|newspaper=Hawaii Star Advertiser|date=2012-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Students==\n\n=== Student body ===\nIn 2013, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked the school 25th of 190 Law Schools for \"Most Selective\". In addition, Richardson is recognized for its highly diverse student body. In 2013, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked it 1st of 190 Law Schools for \"Diversity Index,\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-school-diversity-rankings|title=Law School Diversity Programs|last=|first=|date=March 11, 2013|newspaper=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=March 12, 2013}}</ref> while ''Princeton Review'' ranked it \"Best Environment for Minority Students.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/law-school-rankings.aspx|title=The 2014 Edition of the Best 169 Law Schools|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Princeton Review|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Law student pledge ===\nAdopted in 2002 as an aspirational reflection of [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], all Richardson students recite the William S. Richardson School of Law Law Student Pledge , written by late Professor [[Chris Iijima]], before a  Hawaii Supreme Court  Justice during a special ceremony before they begin their legal education.\n[[File:WSRL Oath.JPG|220x220px|thumb|Richardson Students Reciting Law Student Pledge At [[Hawaii Supreme Court]]]]\n\nThe Pledge is:\n\n''In the study of law, I will conscientiously prepare myself;''\n\n''To advance the interests of those I serve before my own,''\n\n''To approach my responsibilities and colleagues with integrity, professionalism, and civility,''\n\n''To guard zealously legal, civil and human rights which are the birthright of all people,''\n\n''And, above all,''\n\n''To endeavor always to seek justice.''\n\n''This I do pledge.''\n\n==Student organizations==\n\nRichardson sponsors numerous student organizations, including:<ref>{{cite web|title= Student Organizations|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/students|work=Students|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n\n*'Ahahui O Hawai'i\n*Advocates For Public Interest Law (APIL)\n*[[American Inns of Court]] (The Hon. James S. Burns Aloha Chapter of the Inns of Court<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.midweek.com/honoring-the-honorable-judge-burns/|title=Honoring The Honorable Judge Burns|last=Boylan|first=Dan|date=April 18, 2012|newspaper=Midweek|accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref>)\n*[[American Bar Association]]-Student Chapter\n*Black Law Student Association (BLSA)\n*Christian Legal Society (CLS)\n*[[Delta Theta Phi]] Legal Fraternity (DTP)\n*Environmental Law Society (ELS)\n[[File:PALSO Lunar New Year Party.jpg|300px|thumb|right|The Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Organization's (PALSO) Annual Lunar New Year Party. PALSO is one of the school's biggest student organizations]]\n*[[Federalist Society]]\n*Filipino Law School Association (FLSA)\n*Hammurabi Legal Forum\n*Hawaii Women's Lawyers\n*La Alianza\n*[[Lambda Legal|Lambda]] Law Student Association\n*Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Organization (PALSO)\n*[[Phi Delta Phi]] International Legal Fraternity\n*Richardson Golf Association\n*Running Group\n*Self Defense Club\n*Soccer Club\n*Street Law\n*Student Animal League Defense Fund (SALDF)\n*[[Student Bar Association]] (SBA)\n*Students With Keiki\n*Sustainable Richardson\n*[[TED (conference)|TED]] Richardson\n\n==Moot Court teams==\n[[File:WSRL Moot.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Richardson Students Competing At The 2012 Native American Law Student Association Competition Finals At [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] in [[Honolulu]]]]\nRichardson fields [[Moot Court]] teams, composed of students, in competitions across many legal areas.<ref>{{cite web|title= Moot Court Teams|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/student-organizations/client-counseling-team|work=Moot Court Teams|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref> In addition, Richardson fields a competitive Client Counseling Team.\n\n=== Moot court teams ===\n* Environmental Moot Court Team\n* Hispanic Moot Court Team\n* Saul Lefkowtiz Intellectual Property Moot Court Team\n* International Environmental Moot Court Team\n* International Negotiations Team\n* Mock Trial Team\n* Native American Moot Court Team\n* [[Philip C. Jessup International Law Moot Court Competition]] Team\n* Robert F. Wagner Labor & Employment Law Moot Court Team\n* Space Law Moot Court Team\n\n==Law school traditions==\n[[File:Ete Bowl I.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Ete Bowl Football Teams]]\nA list of some of Richardson's traditions:\n*'''Student Pledge'''\n:Adopted in 2002 as an aspirational reflection of [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], all Richardson students recite the [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Students|Law Student Pledge]], written by late Professor [[Chris Iijima]], before a [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] Justice during a special ceremony before they begin their legal education.\n* '''Ete Bowl'''\n[[File:Stew Day I.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Stew Day]]\n:Starting in 1978, Richardson\u2014in a tradition that promotes school spirit and camaraderie amongst students\u2014holds a yearly alumnae v. female law students flag football game.<ref>{{cite web|title= Ete Bowl|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/ete-bowls|work=Ete Bowls|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/the-annual-ete-bowl-goes-oemano-a-mano-in-manoa/123|title=The Annual Ete Bowl Goes Mano a Mano|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|newspaper=The Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> The Alumnae (\"Bruzers\") and UH Law Student (\"Etes\") teams are composed entirely of female students, while cheerleaders are composed of male students dressed in drag.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/the-annual-ete-bowl-goes-oemano-a-mano-in-manoa/123|title=The Annual Ete Bowl Goes Mano A Mano|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|newspaper=Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=March 21, 2013}}</ref> \n* '''Stew Day'''\n:Begun by Professor Calvin Pang, every year on Stew Day, the Richardson Faculty dress up in goofy hats and aprons and serve a stew lunch to the students.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Newsletter of the Association of American Law School|journal=Equipoise|date=December 2009|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/sites/www.law.hawaii.edu/files/downloads/Equipoise_Dec_09_LR.pdf}}</ref> Recently added to Stew Day, Professor Pang orchestrated the \"Red Socks Award\" \u2013 in honor of Dean [[Aviam Soifer]], a Boston [[Red Sox]] Fan. H\n\n==Notable alumni==\n'''Politics'''\n\n*[[Colleen Hanabusa]], US Congressional Representative\n*[[Florence T. Nakakuni]], [[United States Attorney for the District of Hawaii]]\n*[[John D. Waihee III]], Former Hawaii Governor\n*[[Duke Aiona]], 10th Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii\n*[[Earl I. Anzai]], Former Hawaii State Attorney General\n*[[Brian Taniguchi]], Hawaii State Senator\n*[[Dwight Takamine]], Hawaii State Senator\n*[[Blake Oshiro]], Majority Leader, Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Quentin Kaw\u0101nanakoa]], Minority Leader Hawaii, House of Representatives\n*[[Della Au Belatti]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Sharon Har]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Scott Nishimoto]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Maile Shimabukuro]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Kirk Caldwell]], Mayor of Honolulu, Hawaii\n*[[Billy Kenoi]], Mayor of Hawaii Island\n*[[Doug Chin]], 14th Attorney General of Hawaii and 13th Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii\n\n'''Judiciary'''\n\n*[[Sabrina McKenna]], Hawaii Supreme Court Justice, Lawyer\n\n'''Academia'''\n\n* [[Mari Matsuda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.law.hawaii.edu/ William S. Richardson School of Law]\n{{University of Hawaii at Manoa}}\n{{University of Hawaii}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Hawaii}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Education in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law school \n| name     = William S. Richardson<br/>School of Law\n| image =  [[File:William S. Richardson School of Law.png|180px]]\n|established  = 1973\n|parent = [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]]\n|type              = Public\n|endowment =\n|parent endowment =\n|head              = [[Aviam Soifer]] \n|students          = 257\n|faculty = 52\n|ranking = 91\n|annual tuition =\n|city              = Honolulu\n|state = HI\n|country = United States\n|coordinates = {{coord|21|17|47|N|157|49|05|W|region:US-HI_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| homepage      =  http://www.law.hawaii.edu/\n| motto             = {{lang|haw|Ma luna a{{okina}}e o na lahui a pau ke ola ke kanaka}} ([[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]])<br />''Above all nations is humanity''\n| aba profile = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=62 William S. Richardson School of Law Profile]\n| logo               = [[File:Richardson Logo.jpg]]\n}}\n\nThe [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] '''William S. Richardson School of Law''' is a public law school located in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]] in [[Honolulu]]. Named after its patriarch, former [[Hawaii State Supreme Court]] [[Chief Justice]] [[William S. Richardson]], a zealous advocate of Hawaiian culture,<ref name=\"Hevesi\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/us/25richardson.html?ref=dennis_hevesi|title=William S. Richardson, Ex-Chief Justice in Hawaii, Dies at 90|last=Hevesi|first=Dennis|date=2010-06-28|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> it is the state's only law school.<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutlawschools.org/lawschool/william-s-richardson-school-of-law|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa (William S. Richardson School of Law)|last=|first=|date=|work=University of Hawaii at Manoa (William S. Richardson School of Law)|publisher=About Law Schools|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309222222/http://www.aboutlawschools.org/lawschool/william-s-richardson-school-of-law/|archive-date=August 9, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRichardson's regime of legal studies places special emphasis on fields of law of particular importance to Hawaii and the surrounding [[Pacific Rim|Pacific]] and [[Asia]]n region, including [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Native Hawaiian Law Certificate|Native Hawaiian Law]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate|Pacific-Asian Legal Studies]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Environmental Law Certificate|Environmental Law]], and [[maritime law]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Aug/24/op/hawaii808240327.html|title=Concern For Others Key To Law School's Mission|last=Mariani-Belding|first=Jeanne|date=August 4, 2008|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202033948/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Aug/24/op/hawaii808240327.html|archive-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA member of the [[Association of american law schools|Association of American Law Schools]] (AALS), the school is accredited by the Council of the Section of Legal Education and Admissions to the Bar of the [[American Bar Association]] (ABA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2011/11/10/university-of-hawaii-law-school.html|title=University of Hawaii Law School Retains ABA Accreditation|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2011|newspaper=Pacific Business News|accessdate=February 19, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010019/http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2011/11/10/university-of-hawaii-law-school.html|archive-date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> It offers a [[Juris Doctor]], with certificates available in [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Native Hawaiian Law Certificate|Native Hawaiian Law]], [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate|Pacific-Asian Legal Studies]], and [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Environmental Law Certificate|Environmental Law]], with students able to matriculate either full-time or part-time. It also offers an Advanced Juris Doctor, for foreign students who have earned a law degree abroad, and a [[LLM]].\n\nFor 2016, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked Richardson as 82nd among the nations law schools.<ref name=\"Above The Law\">{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/03/the-2016-u-s-news-law-school-rankings-are-here/2/|title=The 2016 U.S. News Law School Rankings Are Here!|last1=Zaretsky|first1=Staci|date=March 10, 2015|website=Above The Law|publisher=Above The Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909193346/http://abovethelaw.com:80/2015/03/the-2016-u-s-news-law-school-rankings-are-here/2/|archive-date=September 9, 2017|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>  Richardson's part-time program was ranked 30th.<ref name=\"U.S. News and World Report\">{{cite news|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa -Richardson|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-hawaii-manoa-richardson-03043|accessdate=3 September 2014|publisher=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref>\n\n==William S. Richardson==\n{{Main|William S. Richardson}}\n\nThe establishment of the Law School in 1973, was considered the achievement of former [[Hawaii State Supreme Court]] [[Chief Justice]], [[William S. Richardson]].<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\" /> For many years he had pressed the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] for its creation, arguing that the state would benefit by providing a legal education for its residents that enveloped its cultural customs\u2014because they had the greatest stake in constructing the state's legal traditions going forward as such. At his retirement, the Law School was named in his honor.\n\n==Ethos==\n{{Main|K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe}}\n[[File:Plaque Kanawai Mamalahoe.jpg|300px|thumb|K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe, on a plaque under the [[Kamehameha Statues]].]]\nThe spirit of Richardson's culture as a community devoted to the study of law is manifested in [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], the fundamental precept of Hawaiian law.\n\nOriginating in a royal edict by [[Kamehameha I|King Kamehameha]] I in 1797, galvanizing the [[Kingdom of Hawai'i]]'s legal system, [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], or Law of the Splintered Paddle, was enshrined later in the [[Constitution of Hawaii|Hawaii State Constitution]], Article 9, Section 10.<ref name=\"hawaii1\">[[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]] holds that government should strive for justice and to protect the rights of all of humanity through the rule of law. [http://www.hawaii.edu/uhelp/files/LawOfTheSplinteredPaddle.pdf The Law of the Splintered Paddle: K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]. (PDF). hawaii.edu</ref>\n\nAccording to Hawaiian legend, [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]] was declared by King Kamehameha after an incident where he chased two fishermen who were fishing illegally, when he caught his leg in the reef, and one of the fisherman, Kaleleiki, hit him mightily on the head with a paddle in defense, which broke into pieces. Luckily, Kamehameha was able to escape. Years later, Kamehameha held, when the same fisherman was brought before him to account for the incident, that in the interest of justice he should be released, as he had only been searching for food for his family.<ref name=\"hawaii1\"/>\n\nReflecting [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], the school maintains a \"commitment... to a collaborative community that is deeply committed to the... pursuit of social and economic justice\" for all.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|title=About William S. Richardson School of Law Mission Statement|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/about-us|work=About William S. Richardson School of Law Mission Statement|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-27}}</ref> Reflecting this commitment, its unofficial logo is Kaleleiki, the fisherman.\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:William S. Richardson School of Law, Street View.jpg|220x220px|thumb|University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa Campus With The William S. Richardson School of Law Library In Background]]\n*1968 \u2013 The [[Hawaii State Legislature]] established the William S. Richardson School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|title= William S. Richardson Timeline|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/time-line|work=Timeline|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n*1973 \u2013 Richardson welcomed its first class, including 53 students.\n*1972 \u2013 David Hood appointed Dean.\n*1974 \u2013 The [[American Bar Association]] granted William S. Richardson School of Law provisional accreditation.\n*1976 \u2013 Jerome Dupont appointed Acting Dean.\n*1977 \u2013 Cliff Thompson appointed Dean.\n*1978 \u2013 Richardson holds first [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Law school traditions|Ete Bowl]].\n*1979 \u2013 ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' created.\n\n===1980s===\n*1981 \u2013 Richard Miller appointed Dean.\n*1982 \u2013 The [[American Bar Association]] granted William S. Richardson School of Law full accreditation.\n*1982 \u2013 Richardson sends first [[Moot Court]] Team to competition.\n*1983 \u2013 William S. Richardson School of Law moved into new facilities on the campus of the [[University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa]].\n*1983 \u2013 Richardson Law Library opens.\n*1983 \u2013 Pacific-Asian Legal Studies program begins.\n*1985 \u2013 Jeremy Harrison appointed Dean.\n*1985 \u2013 [[Student Bar Association]] Formed.\n*1987 \u2013 Theschool joins [[United States Supreme Court]] Jurists-In-Residence Program\n\n===1990s===\n\n*1991 \u2013 Elder Law Program formed.\n*1992 \u2013 Environmental Law Certificate established.\n*1995 \u2013 Lawrence Foster appointed Dean.\n*1995 \u2013 Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Certificate established.\n\n===2000s===\n\n*2002 \u2013 Law Student Pledge adopted.\n*2003 \u2013 [[Aviam Soifer]] appointed dean.<ref>{{cite news|last=Espanol|first=Zenaida Serrano|title=Nominee for UH law dean approved|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2003/Mar/15/ln/ln14a.html|accessdate=2011-09-27|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|date=2003-03-15}}</ref>\n*2003 \u2013 [[William S. Richardson School of Law#LLM Degree|LLM]] program started.<ref name=\"aboutlawschools\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2003/02/10/news/index8.html|title=UH To Begin Law For Foreign-Trained Lawyers|last=|first=|date=February 10, 2003|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n*2005 \u2013 [[Native Hawaiians#Ka Huli Ao: Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law|Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law]] established<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/kahuliao|title=Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law {{!}} William S. Richardson School of Law|website=www.law.hawaii.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> through a ''[[Native Hawaiians#Native American Programs Act|Native Hawaiian Education Act]]'' grant.\n*2005 \u2013 Hawaii Innocence Project established.\n*2008 \u2013 Richardson established a part-time evening law program.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Dec/10/br/br8465319720.html|title=UH Law School to launch part-time programs|last=|first=|date=December 10, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=September 27, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404215849/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Dec/10/br/br8465319720.html|archive-date=April 2, 2017}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 Richardson received a grant from [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS Media Holdings]] in [[Seoul, South Korea]] for $200,000 to establish a Korean Law Faculty Fund.<ref name=\"lawfund\">{{cite news|title=University of Hawaii Creates Korean Law Fund|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2009/02/16/daily23.html|accessdate=2012-02-19|newspaper=Pacific Business News|date=2009-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n\n*2010 \u2013 Chief Justice [[William S. Richardson]] died on June 21.<ref name=\"Hevesi\"/>\n*2011 \u2013 Professor Jon Van Dyke died.\n*2016 \u2013 Dean Jeremy Thomas Harrison died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legalnews.com/detroit/1424717|title=Former MSU Law dean dies, 80 > Detroit Legal News|last=|first=|date=May 13, 2016|website=www.legalnews.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n\n===2016===\n* ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked Richardson 82nd amongst its 142 ranked law  schools.<ref name=\"Above The Law\"/> Richardson's part-time program was ranked 30th.<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite web|title=University of Hawaii at Manoa \u2013 Richardson|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-hawaii-manoa-richardson-03043|website=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Richardson's official 2013 ABA-required disclosures, 50.9% of the Class of 2013 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/sites/www.law.hawaii.edu/files/content/ABA%20Employment%20Summary%20Class%202013.pdf|title=Employment Statistics|last=American Bar Association|first=|date=April 9, 2014|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> Richardson's [[Law School Transparency]] under-employment score is 10.2%, indicating the percentage of the class of 2017 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a short-term, part-time, or non-professional job nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/hawaii/2013/|title=University of Hawaii Law School Transparency Report|last=|first=|date=|website=Law School Transparency|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> It is unclear whether the Law School's above-average clerkship placement rate for new graduates is reflected in these numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2012/04/03|title=New Study Ranks Richardson Law School High in Top 20 Law Schools That Help Graduates Find State and Local Clerkships|last=|first=|date=April 12, 2012|website=Richardson School of Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826221706/https://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2012/04/03|archive-date=August 6, 2016|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at the Richardson School of Law for the 2014\u20132015 academic year is $37,934 for Hawaii residents and $57,662 for non-residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/cost-attendance|title=Cost of Attendance}}</ref> Law School Transparency has estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years is $166,060 for residents and $261,639 for non-residents in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/hawaii/costs/2013/|title=University of Hawaii Total Debt|last=|first=|date=|website=Law School Transparency|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>  In July 2016, Richardson was ranked #1 by U.S. News & World Report among American law schools whose alumni have the least debt, at an average of $54,988 for the Class of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/the-short-list-grad-school/articles/2016-07-19/10-law-schools-where-alumni-have-the-least-debt|title=10 Law Schools Where Alumni Have the Least Debt|last=Smith-Barrow|first=Delece|date=July 19, 2016|website=U.S. News and World Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116073122/http://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/the-short-list-grad-school/articles/2016-07-19/10-law-schools-where-alumni-have-the-least-debt|archive-date=January 16, 2017|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Richardson Law Library Entrance 2012-04-20.png|300x300px|right|frame|The William S. Richardson School of Law Library]]\n\n==Institutes, programs & centers==\n\n=== Institutes ===\n*Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law. The Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law was established in June 2006. Its goal is to become an academic center for research and training in the  field of business law in Asia and the Pacific.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/iapbl|title=Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law|last=|first=|date=|work=Institute of Asian-Pacific Business Law|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> The Institute focuses on commercial law, insolvency and secured transactions, corporate law and business transactions, securities, intellectual property, real estate financing, and labor law issues. The Institute's activities facilitate direct exchanges between the academic, legal, and business communities in Hawaii and throughout the Asia-Pacific region.\n*Hammurabi Legal Forum: The Hammurabi Legal Forum for the Rule of Law (HLF) was established in 2008 at the school to aid law schools in Iraq re-invigorate the country's tradition of scholarship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2008/11/10/story6.html|title=UH Students Help Struggling Iraqi Law School|last=Chiem|first=Linda|date=November 9, 2008|newspaper=Pacific Business News|accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref> By providing an  online database of free legal resources, HLF originally sought to provide information on issues that are important to Iraq and the Iraqi legal community. In 2009, the HLF expanded its efforts to assist Rule of Law activities in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq. In 2010, it further expanded its research to incorporate additional regions of the globe, including Afghanistan and the Pacific Region, with a special focus on Timor-Leste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/malamalama/2011/03/pietsch/|title=University of Hawaii professor promotes rule of law in Iraq {{!}} Malamalama, The Magazine of the University of Hawai'i System|last=Char|first=Kymber-Lee|date=March 30, 2011|website=www.hawaii.edu|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Programs ===\n* Hawaii Innocence Project: The Hawaii Innocence Project's mission is to provide [[pro bono]] representation to incarcerated persons who have a credible claim of actual innocence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jan/31/br/br8617503492.html|title=UH Manoa Law School Programs Awarded $18,500|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204948/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jan/31/br/br8617503492.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jun/29/br/br3658941702.html|title=UH Law School's 'Innocence Project' Gets 10K Grant|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182711/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jun/29/br/br3658941702.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n:University of Hawaii Elder Law Program (UHELP): Operating throughout the year, UHELP provides Hawaii's elder community basic legal assistance, advice and information.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/03/ln/FP606030343.html|title=$3.2 Million Settlement Benefits Elders, UH|last=Creamer|first=Beverly|date=June 3, 2006|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182808/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/03/ln/FP606030343.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/uhelp/|title=UHELP Community Services|last=|first=|date=|work=UHELP Community Services|publisher=UHELP|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Centers ===\n*Ka Huli Ao Center for Excellence in Native Hawaiian Law. Established in 2005 through a Native Hawaiian Education Act grant, the Center is an academic center that promotes education, scholarship, community outreach and collaboration on issues of law, culture and justice for Native Hawaiians and other Pacific and Indigenous peoples.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Nov/07/br/br6174253890.html|title=Hawaii Law School Program Receives $630,000 Grant|last=|first=|date=November 7, 2007|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222113/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Nov/07/br/br6174253890.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> The center focuses on education, research and scholarship, community outreach, and the preservation of historical, legal, and traditional and customary materials. It also offers new courses and supports Native Hawaiian and other law students as they pursue legal careers and leadership roles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jun/26/ln/ln11p.html|title=UH Plans Native Hawaiian Law Center|last=Creamer|first=Beverly|date=June 26, 2005|newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser|accessdate=April 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318182609/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jun/26/ln/ln11p.html|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.news.blogs.civilbeat.com/post/49474039062/uhm-native-hawaiian-law-center-unveils-new-publication|title=UHM Native Hawaiian Law Center Unveils New Publication|last=|first=|date=May 2, 2013|website=Civil Beat|publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224103418/http://hawaii.news.blogs.civilbeat.com/post/49474039062/uhm-native-hawaiian-law-center-unveils-new-publication|archive-date=December 24, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref>\n*Hawaii Health Law Policy Center aims to 1) to conduct and disseminate research on health law policy aimed at improving health care access in Hawaii; 2) to serve as a focus for multidisciplinary research, teaching, on health law and policy in the context of Hawaii; and 3) to bring community leaders, health care policymakers, faculty members, and students together to find solutions to health care shortages and other barriers to access in Hawaii's rural, impoverished, or otherwise underserved communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/health-law-policy-center|title=Health Law Policy Center|last=|first=|date=|work=Health Law Policy Center|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Scholarly publications==\n\n=== ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' ===\nThe ''University of Hawaii Law Review'' is a scholarly legal journal run by students that publishes works by jurists, scholars and practitioners. It publishes two issues annually, and hosts a biennial symposium.\n\n=== ''Asian-Pacific Law & Policy Journal'' ===\nThe ''Asian-Pacific Law and Policy Journal''is a biannual [[peer-reviewed]] [[open-access]] [[law journal]] published by the school. It covers issues facing [[Asia]] and the [[Pacific Rim]]. The journal was established in February 2000, with Jim Hitchingham as [[editor-in-chief]] and with assistance and support from Lawrence Foster, Dean of the law school, and professors Ronald Brown and Mark Levin. In addition to its web format, the journal is available through the legal databases [[LexisNexis]] and [[Westlaw]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/law/pals/journal.html|title=ASIAN-PACIFIC LAW & POLICY JOURNAL (APLPJ)|last=|first=|date=|website=manoa.hawaii.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Visiting tribunals & jurist-in-residence programs==\n\n===Visiting tribunals===\n\n====United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit & Hawaii Supreme Court====\n\nEach year, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] sits specially at the school to hear some appeals from the [[United States District Court]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Hawaii|Districts of Hawaii]] and [[District Court of Guam|Guam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ninth Circuit Sitting In Honolulu Includes Visit To University of Hawaii|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/press-release/2009/10/07|work=Press Release|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2013/09/30/9th-us-circuit-court-of-appeals-will.html|title=9th US Circuit Court of Appeals Will Hear Arguments in Honolulu|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Pacific Business News|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] also sits regularly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/115184184.html?id=115184184|title=Hawaii Supreme Court to hear case at UH law school|last=|first=|date=February 3, 2011|newspaper=Honolulu Star Advertiser|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courts.state.hi.us/news_and_reports/press_releases/2011/02/oral_argument_at_law_school.html|title=Hawaii Supreme Court to Hear Oral Argument at Law School|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Hawaii Judiciary|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Jurist-in-residence programs===\n\n====Bright International Jurist-in-Residence Program====\n\nStarted in 2007 under the tutelage of Senior Circuit Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit|United States Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit]], [[Myron Bright|Myron H Bright]], the Bright International Jurist-in-Residence program hosts international jurists to facilitate dialogue with the wider community and the school's faculty and staff.\n\nIn 2007, [[Israel Supreme Court]] judge [[Aharon Barak]] was the visiting scholar. In 2010, the president of the [[International Court of Justice]] [[Hisashi Owada]] served as visiting scholar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caselombardi.com/jurist.html|title=Jurist-In-residence program {{!}} Case Lombardi & Pettit|website=www.caselombardi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\n====U.S. Supreme Court Jurist-in-Residence Program====\n\nInstituted in 1987, with the support of [[Myron H. Bright]], a Senior Circuit Judge for the [[United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit|United States Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit]], Richardson has a [[U.S. Supreme Court]] Jurist-In-Residence Program.  Biannually, a visiting [[U.S. Supreme Court]] Justice presents seminars on current judicial issues as well as teaches classes.<ref>{{cite web|title= US Supreme Court Jurist Residence program|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/us-supreme-court-jurist-residence-program}}</ref> \n[[File:Alito Civ Pro.jpg|300px|thumb|right|[[Samuel Alito|Supreme Court Justice Samuel Alito]] Teaching Richardson Civil Procedure Class, 2011]]\n\n==Faculty==\n\n=== Endowed professorship & faculty chairs ===\n\nThrough the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] Foundation, Richardson has been endowed with several professorships and faculty chairs.\n\n* Benjamin A. Kudo Professor of Law<ref>{{cite web|title=Chairs and Professorships|url=http://www.uhfoundation.org/gift_impact/faculty/chairs_professorships.aspx|work=Chairs and Professorships|publisher=University of Hawaii Foundation|accessdate=2012-02-19}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Inouye|Dan & Maggie Inouye]] Distinguished Chair In Democratic Ideas\n* [[Fred Korematsu|Fred T. Korematsu]] Professorship In Law and Social Justice<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uhfoundation.org/donor_resources/giving_opportunities/korematsu.aspx|title=The Fred T. Korematsu Chair In Law And Social Justice At The William S. Richardson School Of Law|last=|first=|date=April 13, 2012|newspaper=University of Hawaii Foundation|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n* George J Johnson Visiting Professor Endowment\n* Michael J. Marks Distinguished Professor of Business Law<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael J. Marks Distinguished Professorship in Business Law Established|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=4101|work=Michael J.  Marks Distinguished Professorship in Business Law Established|publisher=University of Hawaii|accessdate=2012-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/michael-j-marks-distinguished-professorship-in-business-law-established-at-uh-manoa/123|title=Michael J Marks Distinguished Professorship In Business Law Established At UH Manoa|last=|first=|date=December 20, 2010|newspaper=The Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n* Wallace S. Fujiyama Distinguished Visiting Professor of Law<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=4859|title=Law School January Term Brings Outstanding Scholars To Hawaii|publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref>\n* Carlsmith Ball Faculty Scholar Fund<ref>{{cite news|title=Law Firm Endows Faculty Scholar Fund At UH|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2008/11/10/story6.html|accessdate=2012-02-19|newspaper=Pacific Business News|date=2008-07-30}}</ref>\n* [[SBS (Korea)|SBS Holdings Co]]. Korean Faculty Fund<ref name=\"lawfund\"/>\n\n=== Notable faculty ===\n\nIn 2013,''[[The Princeton Review]]'' ranked the Richardson faculty as the third \"Most Diverse Faculty.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/UniversityofHawaiiatManoaSchoolofLaw.aspx|title=William S. Richardson School of Law|last=|first=|date=March 12, 2013|newspaper=Princeton Review|accessdate=March 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010014250/http://www.princetonreview.com:80/schools/1035770/law/university-hawaii-at-manoa-william-s-richardson-school-law|archive-date=October 10, 2016}}</ref> And, in 2012, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked the school 3rd of 190 Law Schools for \"Smallest Faculty-Student Ratio\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/article/uh-law-school-named-best-minority-students-and-one-nations-top-169-princeton-review|title=UH Law School Named 'Best' For Minority Students|last=|first=|date=October 10, 2013|website=|publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa William S Richardson School of Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103083208/https://www.law.hawaii.edu/article/uh-law-school-named-best-minority-students-and-one-nations-top-169-princeton-review|archive-date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> The faculty is specialized in an array of legal areas.\n\n'''Current notable faculty''':\n* David L. Callies, Scholar of the Law of Real Property\n* Tae-Ung Baik, Former Korean Prisoner of Conscience,<ref>{{cite web|title=South Korea: Prisoner of Conscience Baik Tae-Ung|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/ASA25/024/1993/en|work=South Korea: Prisoner of Conscience Baik Tae-Ung|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=2012-02-25}}</ref> Specialist in International Human Rights Law and Korean Law\n* [[Mari Matsuda]], Activist legal scholar, lawyer, first tenured Female Asian-American law professor\n*[[Randall Roth (professor)|Randall Roth]]\n*[[Richard W. Pollack]]\n*[[Aviam Soifer]], Constitutional law scholar, former Dean of Boston College Law School\n*[[Eric Yamamoto]], Korematsu Professor of Law and Social Justice,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=5037|title=Law School Professor Eric Yamamoto Awarded Korematsu Professorship|last=|first=|date=April 17, 2012|publisher=University of Hawaii Manoa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161102152617/http://www.manoa.hawaii.edu/news/article.php?aId=5037|archive-date=November 2, 2016|accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Former faculty'''\n\n*[[Chris Iijima]], Legal scholar, Asian-American civil rights activist, folk singer (Deceased)\n*Jon Van Dyke, Constitutional law scholar, lawyer, activist (Deceased)<ref>{{cite news|last=Dayton|first=Kevin|title=UH Constitutional Law Professor Jon Van Dyke Dies|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/UH_constitutional_law_professor_Jon_Van_Dyke_dies.html?id=134764028|accessdate=2011-11-30|newspaper=Hawaii Star Advertiser|date=2012-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Students==\n\n=== Student body ===\nIn 2013, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked the school 25th of 190 Law Schools for \"Most Selective\". In addition, Richardson is recognized for its highly diverse student body. In 2013, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked it 1st of 190 Law Schools for \"Diversity Index,\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-school-diversity-rankings|title=Law School Diversity Programs|last=|first=|date=March 11, 2013|newspaper=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=March 12, 2013}}</ref> while ''Princeton Review'' ranked it \"Best Environment for Minority Students.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/law-school-rankings.aspx|title=The 2014 Edition of the Best 169 Law Schools|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Princeton Review|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Law student pledge ===\nAdopted in 2002 as an aspirational reflection of [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], all Richardson students recite the William S. Richardson School of Law Law Student Pledge , written by late Professor [[Chris Iijima]], before a  Hawaii Supreme Court  Justice during a special ceremony before they begin their legal education.\n[[File:WSRL Oath.JPG|220x220px|thumb|Richardson Students Reciting Law Student Pledge At [[Hawaii Supreme Court]]]]\n\nThe Pledge is:\n\n''In the study of law, I will conscientiously prepare myself;''\n\n''To advance the interests of those I serve before my own,''\n\n''To approach my responsibilities and colleagues with integrity, professionalism, and civility,''\n\n''To guard zealously legal, civil and human rights which are the birthright of all people,''\n\n''And, above all,''\n\n''To endeavor always to seek justice.''\n\n''This I do pledge.''\n\n==Student organizations==\n\nRichardson sponsors numerous student organizations, including:<ref>{{cite web|title= Student Organizations|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/students|work=Students|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n\n*'Ahahui O Hawai'i\n*Advocates For Public Interest Law (APIL)\n*[[American Inns of Court]] (The Hon. James S. Burns Aloha Chapter of the Inns of Court<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.midweek.com/honoring-the-honorable-judge-burns/|title=Honoring The Honorable Judge Burns|last=Boylan|first=Dan|date=April 18, 2012|newspaper=Midweek|accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref>)\n*[[American Bar Association]]-Student Chapter\n*Black Law Student Association (BLSA)\n*Christian Legal Society (CLS)\n*[[Delta Theta Phi]] Legal Fraternity (DTP)\n*Environmental Law Society (ELS)\n[[File:PALSO Lunar New Year Party.jpg|300px|thumb|right|The Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Organization's (PALSO) Annual Lunar New Year Party. PALSO is one of the school's biggest student organizations]]\n*[[Federalist Society]]\n*Filipino Law School Association (FLSA)\n*Hammurabi Legal Forum\n*Hawaii Women's Lawyers\n*La Alianza\n*[[Lambda Legal|Lambda]] Law Student Association\n*Pacific-Asian Legal Studies Organization (PALSO)\n*[[Phi Delta Phi]] International Legal Fraternity\n*Richardson Golf Association\n*Running Group\n*Self Defense Club\n*Soccer Club\n*Street Law\n*Student Animal League Defense Fund (SALDF)\n*[[Student Bar Association]] (SBA)\n*Students With Keiki\n*Sustainable Richardson\n*[[TED (conference)|TED]] Richardson\n\n==Moot Court teams==\n[[File:WSRL Moot.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Richardson Students Competing At The 2012 Native American Law Student Association Competition Finals At [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] in [[Honolulu]]]]\nRichardson fields [[Moot Court]] teams, composed of students, in competitions across many legal areas.<ref>{{cite web|title= Moot Court Teams|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/student-organizations/client-counseling-team|work=Moot Court Teams|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref> In addition, Richardson fields a competitive Client Counseling Team.\n\n=== Moot court teams ===\n* Environmental Moot Court Team\n* Hispanic Moot Court Team\n* Saul Lefkowtiz Intellectual Property Moot Court Team\n* International Environmental Moot Court Team\n* International Negotiations Team\n* Mock Trial Team\n* Native American Moot Court Team\n* [[Philip C. Jessup International Law Moot Court Competition]] Team\n* Robert F. Wagner Labor & Employment Law Moot Court Team\n* Space Law Moot Court Team\n\n==Law school traditions==\n[[File:Ete Bowl I.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Ete Bowl Football Teams]]\nA list of some of Richardson's traditions:\n*'''Student Pledge'''\n:Adopted in 2002 as an aspirational reflection of [[K\u0101n\u0101wai M\u0101malahoe]], all Richardson students recite the [[William S. Richardson School of Law#Students|Law Student Pledge]], written by late Professor [[Chris Iijima]], before a [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] Justice during a special ceremony before they begin their legal education.\n* '''Ete Bowl'''\n[[File:Stew Day I.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Stew Day]]\n:Starting in 1978, Richardson\u2014in a tradition that promotes school spirit and camaraderie amongst students\u2014holds a yearly alumnae v. female law students flag football game.<ref>{{cite web|title= Ete Bowl|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/ete-bowls|work=Ete Bowls|publisher=William S. Richardson School of Law|accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/the-annual-ete-bowl-goes-oemano-a-mano-in-manoa/123|title=The Annual Ete Bowl Goes Mano a Mano|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|newspaper=The Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> The Alumnae (\"Bruzers\") and UH Law Student (\"Etes\") teams are composed entirely of female students, while cheerleaders are composed of male students dressed in drag.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/the-annual-ete-bowl-goes-oemano-a-mano-in-manoa/123|title=The Annual Ete Bowl Goes Mano A Mano|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2012|newspaper=Hawaii Reporter|accessdate=March 21, 2013}}</ref> \n* '''Stew Day'''\n:Begun by Professor Calvin Pang, every year on Stew Day, the Richardson Faculty dress up in goofy hats and aprons and serve a stew lunch to the students.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Newsletter of the Association of American Law School|journal=Equipoise|date=December 2009|url=http://www.law.hawaii.edu/sites/www.law.hawaii.edu/files/downloads/Equipoise_Dec_09_LR.pdf}}</ref> Recently added to Stew Day, Professor Pang orchestrated the \"Red Socks Award\" \u2013 in honor of Dean [[Aviam Soifer]], a Boston [[Red Sox]] Fan. H\n\n==Notable alumni==\n'''Politics'''\n\n*[[Colleen Hanabusa]], US Congressional Representative\n*[[Florence T. Nakakuni]], [[United States Attorney for the District of Hawaii]]\n*[[John D. Waihee III]], Former Hawaii Governor\n*[[Duke Aiona]], 10th Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii\n*[[Earl I. Anzai]], Former Hawaii State Attorney General\n*[[Brian Taniguchi]], Hawaii State Senator\n*[[Dwight Takamine]], Hawaii State Senator\n*[[Blake Oshiro]], Majority Leader, Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Quentin Kaw\u0101nanakoa]], Minority Leader Hawaii, House of Representatives\n*[[Della Au Belatti]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Sharon Har]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Scott Nishimoto]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Maile Shimabukuro]], Hawaii House of Representatives\n*[[Kirk Caldwell]], Mayor of Honolulu, Hawaii\n*[[Billy Kenoi]], Mayor of Hawaii Island\n*[[Doug Chin]], 14th Attorney General of Hawaii and 13th Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii\n\n'''Judiciary'''\n\n*[[Sabrina McKenna]], Hawaii Supreme Court Justice, Lawyer\n\n'''Academia'''\n\n* [[Mari Matsuda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.law.hawaii.edu/ William S. Richardson School of Law]\n{{University of Hawaii at Manoa}}\n{{University of Hawaii}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Hawaii}}\n\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Education in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_S._Richardson_School_of_Law"}
{"title_page": "William & Mary Law School", "text_new": "{{Infobox law school\n| name             = Marshall\u2013Wythe School of Law\n| image            = William and Mary Law School seal.png\n| image_size       = 150px\n| alt              =\n| caption          = [[Seal (emblem)|Seal]] of the school\n| motto            = \n| parent           = [[College of William & Mary]]\n| established      = 1779\n| type             = [[Public university|Public]]\n | endowment      = $150 million\n | parent endowment =$1.023 billion\n| dean             = [[Davison M. Douglas]]\n| city             = [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]]\n| state            = [[Virginia]]\n| country          = U.S.\n| coordinates      = {{Coord|37|15|55|N|76|42|18|W|display=inline,title}}\n| students         = 625\n| faculty          = \n| ranking          = 31st (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=William & Mary Law School |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/college-of-william-and-mary-03160 |website=U.S. News & World Report \u2013 Best Law Schools |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n| bar pass rate    = \n| website          = [http://www.law.wm.edu/ www.law.wm.edu]\n| aba profile      = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=172 ABA Profile]\n| logo             = William_and_Mary_Law_School_Logo.png\n| logo_size        =\n| logo_alt         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Marshall\u2013Wythe School of Law at the College of William & Mary''', commonly referred to as '''William & Mary Law School''', is the oldest [[law school]] in the United States. Located in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], Virginia, it is a part of [[College of William & Mary|William & Mary]], the second oldest college and first university in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/about/index.php |title=William & Mary - About |publisher=Wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> The Law School has an enrollment of 645 full-time students (in 2018\u201319) seeking a [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) or an LL.M. in the American Legal System, a two or three semester program for lawyers trained outside the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.wm.edu/about/factoids/index.php |title=At a Glance |publisher=law.wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWilliam & Mary Law School was founded in 1779 at the impetus of [[Governor of Virginia|Virginia Governor]] [[Thomas Jefferson]], an alumnus of the university, during the reorganization of the originally royal institution, transforming the college of William and Mary into the first university in the United States.  At Jefferson's urging, the governing board of visitors of William & Mary established a chair of law and appointed [[George Wythe]], a signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], delegate to the [[Philadelphia Convention]], and Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]], its first holder. (In the English-speaking world, older law professorships include the chair at [[Oxford University]], first held by [[William Blackstone]], the chair at [[Edinburgh University]]'s School of Law (1709), and the [[Regius Professor of Law (Glasgow)|Regius Chair of Law]] at [[Glasgow University]]). [[File:WilliamandMaryLawSchoolStatue.JPG|200px|thumb|right|Statue of Marshall and Wythe at the entrance of the Law School]]\n\nBefore filling the chair of law at William & Mary, Wythe tutored numerous students in the subject, [[Thomas Jefferson]] and [[James Monroe]] among them. [[John Marshall]], who became [[Chief Justice of the United States]] in 1801, received his only formal legal education when he attended Wythe's lectures at William & Mary in 1780. [[St. George Tucker]], who succeeded Wythe as Professor of Law and edited the seminal early American edition of [[Blackstone's Commentaries]], also was one of Wythe's students.\n\nThe growth of the Law School was halted abruptly by the beginning of the [[American Civil War]]. The start of military campaigns on the Virginia Peninsula compelled William & Mary to close its doors. It would be another sixty years before the historical priority in law could be revived in a modern program that is now nearly ninety years old.\n\nAfter William & Mary Law School was reopened early in the twentieth century, it was moved around the main campus of the university to several different buildings in succession.  In 1980, the School was moved to its current location on the outskirts of [[Colonial Williamsburg]], a short distance from the main campus.  The building has been renovated several times since 1980, with the addition of a new wing of classrooms and renovation of older classrooms in 2000, the opening of the [[Henry C. Wolf Law Library]], the construction of a new admission suite, and the addition of the James A. and Robin L. Hixon Center for Experiential Learning and Leadership (dedicated in 2017).\n\n[[W. Taylor Reveley III]], formerly managing partner of the law firm of [[Hunton & Williams]], is a former dean of the Law School. He served as the 27th president of William & Mary from September 5, 2008 to June 30, 2018, after serving as interim president since February 2008.  Davison M. Douglas (J.D., Ph.D., M.Phil., M.A., M.A.R.), a nationally renowned legal historian, is the current dean.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whitson |first=Brian |url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2009/davison-m.-douglas-named-dean-of-william--mary-law-school%20001.php |title=William & Mary - Davison M. Douglas named Dean of William & Mary Law School |publisher=Wm.edu |date=2009-03-20 |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\nThe former chancellor of William & Mary, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], delivered commencement remarks to the graduating class of the Law School in 2006, 2008 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peebles |first=Katie |url=http://law.wm.edu/news/stories/2010/oconnor-commencement-speaker.php |title=William & Mary Law - O'Connor to Deliver Commencement Address; Will Also Receive Marshall-Wythe Medallion |publisher=Law.wm.edu |date=2010-04-16 |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Cost of attendance==\nTuition at William & Mary for the 2019-20 academic year was $35,000 for Virginia residents and $44,000 for non-residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/admissions/jdprograms/cost/index.php |title=Cost of Law School}}</ref> Approximately 88% of students received financial aid (2017). [[Law School Transparency]] estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years, based on data from the 2018-2019 academic year, is $197,520 for residents; the estimated cost for non-residents is $229,557.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/wm/costs/2013/ |title=William and Mary Profile}}</ref>\n\n==Employment==\nAccording to William & Mary's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 80% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required, non-school funded employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wm.edu/careerservices/documents/wm_classof18_aba_employment_summary.pdf |title=Employment Summary for 2018 Graduates}}</ref>\n\nWilliam & Mary's Law School Transparency under-employment score is 10%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation, with 0%  of the class in school-funded jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lstreports.com/schools/wm/jobs/ |title=William and Mary Profile}}</ref>\n\n== Ranking ==\nW&M Law was ranked 24th on the [[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]] ranking in 2019.\n[[U.S. News]] ranked W&M Law as tied for the 31st place in their latest 2021 rankings of the nation's law schools.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/college-of-william-and-mary-03160 |title=Best Law School Rankings &#124; Law Program Rankings &#124; US News |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> For the Class of 2022 (enrolled as of August 19, 2019), the median undergraduate GPA was 3.76 and the median LSAT score was 163.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wm.edu/admissions/jdprograms/facts-figures/classprofile/index.php |title=Class of 2020, William & Mary Law School}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n* William & Mary Law School offers institutes and programs such as the Center for Comparative Legal Studies and Post-Conflict Peacebuilding, the Center for Legal and Court Technology, the Center for the Study of Law and Markets, the Dunn Civil Liberties Project, the Election Law Program, the Human Security Law Center, the Institute of Bill of Rights Law, and the Property Rights Project.\n* The annual Supreme Court Preview of the Institute of Bill of Rights Law brings journalists and academics together each fall for an analysis of key cases on the Court's docket for the new term. \n* The Lewis B. Puller, Jr. Veteran's Benefits Clinic provides students (under the supervision of staff attorneys) with the opportunity to ensure that veterans receive the benefits which they are entitled to as a matter of law and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/14/va-disability-claims-back-log-could-be-alleviated-with-law-school-pro-bono-clinics/|title=June, Daniel, \"VA Disability Claims Back Log Could be Alleviated with Law School Pro Bono Clinics \"|author=Daniel June|date=14 May 2013|work=JD Journal|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref> Other clinics include Appellate and Supreme Court Clinic, Business Law Clinic, Domestic Violence Clinic, Elder Law Clinic, Federal Tax Clinic, Innocence Project Clinic, Special Education Advocacy Clinic, Virginia Coastal Policy Clinic, and Immigration Clinic.\n* Journals include the ''William & Mary Law Review,'' the ''Bill of Rights Journal'', ''William & Mary Environmental Law and Policy Review'', ''William & Mary Journal of Race, Gender, and Social Justice,'' and ''Business Law Review''.\n* The school's McGlothlin Courtroom is home to the Center for Legal and Court Technology, a joint program of the School and the National Center for State Courts. The mission of the project is to use technology to improve the administration of justice and the legal systems of the world.\n* Created in 2005 as a joint venture of the National Center for State Courts and the Law School, the Election Law Program was intended to provide practical assistance to state court judges in the United States who are called upon to resolve difficult election law disputes.  It has since been expanded to include a student Election Law Society. \n* The George Wythe Society of Citizen Lawyers is a civic leadership program, formed in the fall of 2005, to recognize and encourage community service and civic participation by members of the student body.\n* The Human Rights and National Security Law Program focuses on the interplay between national defense and the protection of civil rights. The Program's Distinguished Lecture Series and co-sponsored symposia bring experts to campus each semester to foster discussion and debate about on-going and emerging issues.\n* The Center for the Study of Law and Markets seeks to advance the understanding of the role of legal institutions in promoting well-functioning markets in a free society.\n* The Center for Comparative Legal Studies and Post-Conflict Peacebuilding bridges the gap between resources available at academic institutions and the need for them in the field by rule of law actors engaged in post-conflict reconstruction efforts. The Center serves as a focal point for the law school\u2019s international and comparative legal and policy research and programming and sponsors summer international internships in developing and post-conflict countries around the world.\n* The Institute of Bill of Rights Law engages in study of the Bill of Rights and sponsors a variety of lectures, conferences, and publications to examine Constitutional issues.\n* The William & Mary Property Rights Project encourages scholarly study of the role that property rights play in society.  The Project's annual [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Conference]] explores recent developments in areas such as takings litigation and takings law.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Dennis L. Beck]] (William & Mary 1969, Law 1972), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of California (1990\u20132012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caed.uscourts.gov/caed/staticOther/page_633.htm|title = Magistrate Judge Dennis L. Beck (DLB)| publisher=United States District Court |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[John L. Brownlee]] (Law 1994), former U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Virginia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hklaw.com/John-Brownlee/|title =John L. Brownlee Partner| publisher=Holland & Knight |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Ronald L. Buckwalter]] (Law 1962), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]] (1990\u20132003)\n* [[William H. Cabell]] (Law 1793), received first baccalaureate in law granted in America, governor of Virginia (1805\u20131808), justice of the Supreme Court of Virginia (1811\u20131851)<ref>{{cite web|title=William H. Cabell|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_virginia/col2-content/main-content-list/title_cabell_william.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Cantor]] (Law 1988), U.S. House of Representatives, Virginia (2001\u20132014); [[House Majority Leader]] of [[112th Congress]], 2011<ref>{{cite web|title=Eric Cantor|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001046|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Glen E. Conrad]] (Law 1974), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] (2003-2017), chief judge (2010-2017)\n* [[Clifton L. Corker]] (Law 1993), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Theodore Roosevelt Dalton|Ted Dalton]] (Law 1926), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] (1959\u20131976), chief judge (1960-1971)\n* [[Powhatan Ellis]] (Law 1814), [[United States Senator]] from Mississippi; Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Mississippi]]\n* [[Matt Gaetz]] (Law 2007), U.S. House of Representatives, Florida (2017\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography - Congressman Matt Gaetz|url=https://gaetz.house.gov/issues/biography|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Gurbir Grewal]] (Law 1999), [[Attorney General of New Jersey]]\n* [[D. Arthur Kelsey]] (Law 1985), justice, Supreme Court of Virginia\n* [[Jerry W. Kilgore]] (Law 1986), Attorney General of Virginia (2001\u20132005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=4452|title =Kilgore, Jerry W.| publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Larry W. Lockwood, Jr. (attorney)|Larry W. Lockwood, Jr.]] (Law 1995), Youngest person admitted to Million/Multi-Million Dollar Advocates Forum, obtained largest FELA verdict for a single FELA plaintiff in the 100 years since the enactment of the Federal Employer's Liability Act ($12 million) nine months after graduation<ref>Virginia Lawyers Weekly, \"FELA record of $12M Set In Portsmouth\", March 17, 1997.</ref> followed by a record Maryland Verdict,<ref>The Daily Record, Injured Railroad Wins $750,000, case in Railroad-Friendly Western Md. May Set Record, October 27, 1997</ref> and several other verdicts in cutting edge injury cases.<ref>Richmond Times Dispatch, from trials to trial lawyer, tenacity helped him persevere, July 24, 2001</ref>\n* [[James Murray Mason]] (Law 1820), member of the U.S. House of Representatives (1837\u20131839); United States Senator from Virginia (1847\u20131861)<ref>{{cite web|title=James Murray Mason|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000216|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[John Marshall]], 4th [[Chief Justice of the United States]]\n* [[Haldane Robert Mayer]] (Law 1971), judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (1987\u2013present; chief judge of the Federal Circuit, 1997\u20132004)<ref>{{cite web|title=Haldane Robert Mayer|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1510&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Tommy Miller (judge)|Tommy Miller]] (Law 1973), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (1987; announced his retirement in 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.troutmansanders.com/tom_miller/|title =John Thomas Miller Jr.\n| publisher=Troutman Sanders |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Douglas E. Miller (judge)|Doug Miller]] (Law 1995), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (2009\u2013present   ) {{Citation needed|date= January 2013}}<!--& Mary School of Law-->\n* [[LeRoy F. Millette, Jr.|LeRoy Francis Millette, Jr.]] (William & Mary 1971, Law 1974), justice Supreme Court of Virginia (2009\u2013present )\n* [[Lewis Burwell Puller, Jr.]] (William & Mary 1967, Law 1974), Vietnam veteran (Lt., [[USMC]] ([[Silver Star]], two [[Purple Heart]]s, the [[Navy Commendation Medal]] and the [[Vietnam Cross of Gallantry]]) and [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning author.  The William & Mary Law School's Veteran's Benefit Clinic is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/academics/programs/jd/electives/clinics/veterans/ |title=William & Mary Law - Lewis B. Puller, Jr. Veterans Benefits Clinic |publisher=Law.wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n*[[Steve Salbu]] (JD), dean emeritus of the [[Scheller College of Business]] at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] (2006-2014).<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Salbu Cecil B. Day Chair in Business Ethics, Professor|url=https://www.scheller.gatech.edu/directory/faculty/salbu/index.html|website=Scheller College of Business|publisher=Georgia Institute of Technology|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Robert E. Scott]] (Law 1968), law professor at [[Columbia Law School]], dean of [[University of Virginia]] Law School (1991\u20132001), and fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert E. Scott|url=http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2004_fall/scott_tj.htm|publisher=the University of Virginia|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Rebecca Beach Smith]], (William & Mary 1971, Law 1979), Chief District Judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (2011-2018) \n* [[Henry St. George Tucker (University of Virginia professor)|Henry St. George Tucker]] (William & Mary 1798, Law 1801), professor of law at William & Mary (1801\u20131804), justice of the Supreme Court of Virginia (1824\u20131831), remembered for editing the American edition of Blackstone's ''Commentaries''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry St. George Tucker|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000398|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Jennifer Wexton]], (Law 1995), U.S. House of Representatives, Virginia (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=About - Representative Jennifer Wexton|url=https://wexton.house.gov/about|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Susan Davis Wigenton]], (Law 1987), District Judge, [[United States District Court for the District of New Jersey]], (2006\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njd.uscourts.gov/content/susan-d-wigenton|title=Susan D. Wigenton|publisher=|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Henry C. Wolf]] (William & Mary 1964, Law 1966), former chief financial officer and vice chairman of [[Norfolk Southern Corporation]], former William & Mary rector, benefactor of the [[Henry C. Wolf Law Library]] at the Law School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/archive/2009/henry-c.-wolf-64,-j.d.-66-elected-rector-of-william--mary-123.php |title =Henry C. Wolf '64, J.D. '66 elected Rector of W&M| publisher=The College of William & MaryWilliamsburg, VA |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty members==\n* [[William Van Alstyne]]\n* [[Mitchell Reiss]]\n* [[W. Taylor Reveley, III]]\n* [[Lan Cao]]\n* [[George Wythe]]\n* [[William B. Spong, Jr.]]\n*Peter Alces\n\n==Law journals==\n* ''William & Mary [[Law Review]]'', twenty-fourth-ranked general law journal in the United States, based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Bill of Rights Journal'', third-ranked [[constitutional law]] journal in the United States, based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Environmental Law and Policy Review'', thirteenth-ranked law journal in the United States in [[United States energy law|energy law]] based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Journal of Race, Gender, and Social Justice'', fifth-ranked law journal in the United States among gender, women, and sexuality law journals.\n* ''William & Mary Business Law Review'', sixth-ranked law journal in the United States among [[United States corporate law|corporate law]] journals.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[I Am the College of William and Mary]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://law.wm.edu/ William and Mary Law School]\n{{The College of William & Mary}}\n{{Law Schools of the Mid-Atlantic States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:William and Mary}}\n[[Category:Law schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary schools and programs|Law]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1770s]]\n[[Category:1779 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law school\n| name             = Marshall\u2013Wythe School of Law\n| image            = William and Mary Law School seal.png\n| image_size       = 150px\n| alt              =\n| caption          = [[Seal (emblem)|Seal]] of the school\n| motto            = \n| parent           = [[College of William & Mary]]\n| established      = 1779\n| type             = [[Public university|Public]]\n | endowment      = $150 million\n | parent endowment =$1.023 billion\n| dean             = [[Davison M. Douglas]]\n| city             = [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]]\n| state            = [[Virginia]]\n| country          = U.S.\n| coordinates      = {{Coord|37|15|55|N|76|42|18|W|display=inline,title}}\n| students         = 625\n| faculty          = \n| ranking          = 31st (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=William & Mary Law School |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/college-of-william-and-mary-03160 |website=U.S. News & World Report \u2013 Best Law Schools |accessdate=23 March 2020}} </ref>\n| bar pass rate    = \n| website          = [http://www.law.wm.edu/ www.law.wm.edu]\n| aba profile      = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage.aspx?sid=172 ABA Profile]\n| logo             = William_and_Mary_Law_School_Logo.png\n| logo_size        =\n| logo_alt         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Marshall\u2013Wythe School of Law at the College of William & Mary''', commonly referred to as '''William & Mary Law School''', is the oldest [[law school]] in the United States. Located in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], Virginia, it is a part of [[College of William & Mary|William & Mary]], the second oldest college and first university in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/about/index.php |title=William & Mary - About |publisher=Wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> The Law School has an enrollment of 645 full-time students (in 2018\u201319) seeking a [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) or an LL.M. in the American Legal System, a two or three semester program for lawyers trained outside the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.wm.edu/about/factoids/index.php |title=At a Glance |publisher=law.wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWilliam & Mary Law School was founded in 1779 at the impetus of [[Governor of Virginia|Virginia Governor]] [[Thomas Jefferson]], an alumnus of the university, during the reorganization of the originally royal institution, transforming the college of William and Mary into the first university in the United States.  At Jefferson's urging, the governing board of visitors of William & Mary established a chair of law and appointed [[George Wythe]], a signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]], delegate to the [[Philadelphia Convention]], and Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]], its first holder. (In the English-speaking world, older law professorships include the chair at [[Oxford University]], first held by [[William Blackstone]], the chair at [[Edinburgh University]]'s School of Law (1709), and the [[Regius Professor of Law (Glasgow)|Regius Chair of Law]] at [[Glasgow University]]). [[File:WilliamandMaryLawSchoolStatue.JPG|200px|thumb|right|Statue of Marshall and Wythe at the entrance of the Law School]]\n\nBefore filling the chair of law at William & Mary, Wythe tutored numerous students in the subject, [[Thomas Jefferson]] and [[James Monroe]] among them. [[John Marshall]], who became [[Chief Justice of the United States]] in 1801, received his only formal legal education when he attended Wythe's lectures at William & Mary in 1780. [[St. George Tucker]], who succeeded Wythe as Professor of Law and edited the seminal early American edition of [[Blackstone's Commentaries]], also was one of Wythe's students.\n\nThe growth of the Law School was halted abruptly by the beginning of the [[American Civil War]]. The start of military campaigns on the Virginia Peninsula compelled William & Mary to close its doors. It would be another sixty years before the historical priority in law could be revived in a modern program that is now nearly ninety years old.\n\nAfter William & Mary Law School was reopened early in the twentieth century, it was moved around the main campus of the university to several different buildings in succession.  In 1980, the School was moved to its current location on the outskirts of [[Colonial Williamsburg]], a short distance from the main campus.  The building has been renovated several times since 1980, with the addition of a new wing of classrooms and renovation of older classrooms in 2000, the opening of the [[Henry C. Wolf Law Library]], the construction of a new admission suite, and the addition of the James A. and Robin L. Hixon Center for Experiential Learning and Leadership (dedicated in 2017).\n\n[[W. Taylor Reveley III]], formerly managing partner of the law firm of [[Hunton & Williams]], is a former dean of the Law School. He served as the 27th president of William & Mary from September 5, 2008 to June 30, 2018, after serving as interim president since February 2008.  Davison M. Douglas (J.D., Ph.D., M.Phil., M.A., M.A.R.), a nationally renowned legal historian, is the current dean.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whitson |first=Brian |url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2009/davison-m.-douglas-named-dean-of-william--mary-law-school%20001.php |title=William & Mary - Davison M. Douglas named Dean of William & Mary Law School |publisher=Wm.edu |date=2009-03-20 |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\nThe former chancellor of William & Mary, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], delivered commencement remarks to the graduating class of the Law School in 2006, 2008 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peebles |first=Katie |url=http://law.wm.edu/news/stories/2010/oconnor-commencement-speaker.php |title=William & Mary Law - O'Connor to Deliver Commencement Address; Will Also Receive Marshall-Wythe Medallion |publisher=Law.wm.edu |date=2010-04-16 |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Cost of attendance==\nTuition at William & Mary for the 2019-20 academic year was $35,000 for Virginia residents and $44,000 for non-residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/admissions/jdprograms/cost/index.php |title=Cost of Law School}}</ref> Approximately 88% of students received financial aid (2017). [[Law School Transparency]] estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years, based on data from the 2018-2019 academic year, is $197,520 for residents; the estimated cost for non-residents is $229,557.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/wm/costs/2013/ |title=William and Mary Profile}}</ref>\n\n==Employment==\nAccording to William & Mary's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 80% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required, non-school funded employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wm.edu/careerservices/documents/wm_classof18_aba_employment_summary.pdf |title=Employment Summary for 2018 Graduates}}</ref>\n\nWilliam & Mary's Law School Transparency under-employment score is 10%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation, with 0%  of the class in school-funded jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lstreports.com/schools/wm/jobs/ |title=William and Mary Profile}}</ref>\n\n== Ranking ==\nW&M Law was ranked 24th on the [[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]] ranking in 2019.\n[[U.S. News]] ranked W&M Law as tied for the 31st place in their latest 2021 rankings of the nation's law schools.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/college-of-william-and-mary-03160 |title=Best Law School Rankings &#124; Law Program Rankings &#124; US News |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref> For the Class of 2022 (enrolled as of August 19, 2019), the median undergraduate GPA was 3.76 and the median LSAT score was 163.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wm.edu/admissions/jdprograms/facts-figures/classprofile/index.php |title=Class of 2020, William & Mary Law School}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n* William & Mary Law School offers institutes and programs such as the Center for Comparative Legal Studies and Post-Conflict Peacebuilding, the Center for Legal and Court Technology, the Center for the Study of Law and Markets, the Dunn Civil Liberties Project, the Election Law Program, the Human Security Law Center, the Institute of Bill of Rights Law, and the Property Rights Project.\n* The annual Supreme Court Preview of the Institute of Bill of Rights Law brings journalists and academics together each fall for an analysis of key cases on the Court's docket for the new term. \n* The Lewis B. Puller, Jr. Veteran's Benefits Clinic provides students (under the supervision of staff attorneys) with the opportunity to ensure that veterans receive the benefits which they are entitled to as a matter of law and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2013/05/14/va-disability-claims-back-log-could-be-alleviated-with-law-school-pro-bono-clinics/|title=June, Daniel, \"VA Disability Claims Back Log Could be Alleviated with Law School Pro Bono Clinics \"|author=Daniel June|date=14 May 2013|work=JD Journal|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref> Other clinics include Appellate and Supreme Court Clinic, Business Law Clinic, Domestic Violence Clinic, Elder Law Clinic, Federal Tax Clinic, Innocence Project Clinic, Special Education Advocacy Clinic, Virginia Coastal Policy Clinic, and Immigration Clinic.\n* Journals include the ''William & Mary Law Review,'' the ''Bill of Rights Journal'', ''William & Mary Environmental Law and Policy Review'', ''William & Mary Journal of Race, Gender, and Social Justice,'' and ''Business Law Review''.\n* The school's McGlothlin Courtroom is home to the Center for Legal and Court Technology, a joint program of the School and the National Center for State Courts. The mission of the project is to use technology to improve the administration of justice and the legal systems of the world.\n* Created in 2005 as a joint venture of the National Center for State Courts and the Law School, the Election Law Program was intended to provide practical assistance to state court judges in the United States who are called upon to resolve difficult election law disputes.  It has since been expanded to include a student Election Law Society. \n* The George Wythe Society of Citizen Lawyers is a civic leadership program, formed in the fall of 2005, to recognize and encourage community service and civic participation by members of the student body.\n* The Human Rights and National Security Law Program focuses on the interplay between national defense and the protection of civil rights. The Program's Distinguished Lecture Series and co-sponsored symposia bring experts to campus each semester to foster discussion and debate about on-going and emerging issues.\n* The Center for the Study of Law and Markets seeks to advance the understanding of the role of legal institutions in promoting well-functioning markets in a free society.\n* The Center for Comparative Legal Studies and Post-Conflict Peacebuilding bridges the gap between resources available at academic institutions and the need for them in the field by rule of law actors engaged in post-conflict reconstruction efforts. The Center serves as a focal point for the law school\u2019s international and comparative legal and policy research and programming and sponsors summer international internships in developing and post-conflict countries around the world.\n* The Institute of Bill of Rights Law engages in study of the Bill of Rights and sponsors a variety of lectures, conferences, and publications to examine Constitutional issues.\n* The William & Mary Property Rights Project encourages scholarly study of the role that property rights play in society.  The Project's annual [[Brigham-Kanner Property Rights Conference]] explores recent developments in areas such as takings litigation and takings law.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Dennis L. Beck]] (William & Mary 1969, Law 1972), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of California (1990\u20132012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caed.uscourts.gov/caed/staticOther/page_633.htm|title = Magistrate Judge Dennis L. Beck (DLB)| publisher=United States District Court |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[John L. Brownlee]] (Law 1994), former U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Virginia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hklaw.com/John-Brownlee/|title =John L. Brownlee Partner| publisher=Holland & Knight |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Ronald L. Buckwalter]] (Law 1962), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]] (1990\u20132003)\n* [[William H. Cabell]] (Law 1793), received first baccalaureate in law granted in America, governor of Virginia (1805\u20131808), justice of the Supreme Court of Virginia (1811\u20131851)<ref>{{cite web|title=William H. Cabell|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_virginia/col2-content/main-content-list/title_cabell_william.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Cantor]] (Law 1988), U.S. House of Representatives, Virginia (2001\u20132014); [[House Majority Leader]] of [[112th Congress]], 2011<ref>{{cite web|title=Eric Cantor|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001046|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Glen E. Conrad]] (Law 1974), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] (2003-2017), chief judge (2010-2017)\n* [[Clifton L. Corker]] (Law 1993), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Theodore Roosevelt Dalton|Ted Dalton]] (Law 1926), judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] (1959\u20131976), chief judge (1960-1971)\n* [[Powhatan Ellis]] (Law 1814), [[United States Senator]] from Mississippi; Judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Mississippi]]\n* [[Matt Gaetz]] (Law 2007), U.S. House of Representatives, Florida (2017\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography - Congressman Matt Gaetz|url=https://gaetz.house.gov/issues/biography|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Gurbir Grewal]] (Law 1999), [[Attorney General of New Jersey]]\n* [[D. Arthur Kelsey]] (Law 1985), justice, Supreme Court of Virginia\n* [[Jerry W. Kilgore]] (Law 1986), Attorney General of Virginia (2001\u20132005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=4452|title =Kilgore, Jerry W.| publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Larry W. Lockwood, Jr. (attorney)|Larry W. Lockwood, Jr.]] (Law 1995), Youngest person admitted to Million/Multi-Million Dollar Advocates Forum, obtained largest FELA verdict for a single FELA plaintiff in the 100 years since the enactment of the Federal Employer's Liability Act ($12 million) nine months after graduation<ref>Virginia Lawyers Weekly, \"FELA record of $12M Set In Portsmouth\", March 17, 1997.</ref> followed by a record Maryland Verdict,<ref>The Daily Record, Injured Railroad Wins $750,000, case in Railroad-Friendly Western Md. May Set Record, October 27, 1997</ref> and several other verdicts in cutting edge injury cases.<ref>Richmond Times Dispatch, from trials to trial lawyer, tenacity helped him persevere, July 24, 2001</ref>\n* [[James Murray Mason]] (Law 1820), member of the U.S. House of Representatives (1837\u20131839); United States Senator from Virginia (1847\u20131861)<ref>{{cite web|title=James Murray Mason|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000216|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[John Marshall]], 4th [[Chief Justice of the United States]]\n* [[Haldane Robert Mayer]] (Law 1971), judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (1987\u2013present; chief judge of the Federal Circuit, 1997\u20132004)<ref>{{cite web|title=Haldane Robert Mayer|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1510&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Tommy Miller (judge)|Tommy Miller]] (Law 1973), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (1987; announced his retirement in 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.troutmansanders.com/tom_miller/|title =John Thomas Miller Jr.\n| publisher=Troutman Sanders |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Douglas E. Miller (judge)|Doug Miller]] (Law 1995), magistrate judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (2009\u2013present   ) {{Citation needed|date= January 2013}}<!--& Mary School of Law-->\n* [[LeRoy F. Millette, Jr.|LeRoy Francis Millette, Jr.]] (William & Mary 1971, Law 1974), justice Supreme Court of Virginia (2009\u2013present )\n* [[Lewis Burwell Puller, Jr.]] (William & Mary 1967, Law 1974), Vietnam veteran (Lt., [[USMC]] ([[Silver Star]], two [[Purple Heart]]s, the [[Navy Commendation Medal]] and the [[Vietnam Cross of Gallantry]]) and [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning author.  The William & Mary Law School's Veteran's Benefit Clinic is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wm.edu/academics/programs/jd/electives/clinics/veterans/ |title=William & Mary Law - Lewis B. Puller, Jr. Veterans Benefits Clinic |publisher=Law.wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n*[[Steve Salbu]] (JD), dean emeritus of the [[Scheller College of Business]] at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] (2006-2014).<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Salbu Cecil B. Day Chair in Business Ethics, Professor|url=https://www.scheller.gatech.edu/directory/faculty/salbu/index.html|website=Scheller College of Business|publisher=Georgia Institute of Technology|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Robert E. Scott]] (Law 1968), law professor at [[Columbia Law School]], dean of [[University of Virginia]] Law School (1991\u20132001), and fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert E. Scott|url=http://www.law.virginia.edu/html/news/2004_fall/scott_tj.htm|publisher=the University of Virginia|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Rebecca Beach Smith]], (William & Mary 1971, Law 1979), Chief District Judge of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia (2011-2018) \n* [[Henry St. George Tucker (University of Virginia professor)|Henry St. George Tucker]] (William & Mary 1798, Law 1801), professor of law at William & Mary (1801\u20131804), justice of the Supreme Court of Virginia (1824\u20131831), remembered for editing the American edition of Blackstone's ''Commentaries''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henry St. George Tucker|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000398|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Jennifer Wexton]], (Law 1995), U.S. House of Representatives, Virginia (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=About - Representative Jennifer Wexton|url=https://wexton.house.gov/about|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Susan Davis Wigenton]], (Law 1987), District Judge, [[United States District Court for the District of New Jersey]], (2006\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njd.uscourts.gov/content/susan-d-wigenton|title=Susan D. Wigenton|publisher=|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Henry C. Wolf]] (William & Mary 1964, Law 1966), former chief financial officer and vice chairman of [[Norfolk Southern Corporation]], former William & Mary rector, benefactor of the [[Henry C. Wolf Law Library]] at the Law School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/archive/2009/henry-c.-wolf-64,-j.d.-66-elected-rector-of-william--mary-123.php |title =Henry C. Wolf '64, J.D. '66 elected Rector of W&M| publisher=The College of William & MaryWilliamsburg, VA |accessdate= January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty members==\n* [[William Van Alstyne]]\n* [[Mitchell Reiss]]\n* [[W. Taylor Reveley, III]]\n* [[Lan Cao]]\n* [[George Wythe]]\n* [[William B. Spong, Jr.]]\n*Peter Alces\n\n==Law journals==\n* ''William & Mary [[Law Review]]'', twenty-fourth-ranked general law journal in the United States, based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Bill of Rights Journal'', third-ranked [[constitutional law]] journal in the United States, based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Environmental Law and Policy Review'', thirteenth-ranked law journal in the United States in [[United States energy law|energy law]] based on citations.\n* ''William & Mary Journal of Race, Gender, and Social Justice'', fifth-ranked law journal in the United States among gender, women, and sexuality law journals.\n* ''William & Mary Business Law Review'', sixth-ranked law journal in the United States among [[United States corporate law|corporate law]] journals.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[I Am the College of William and Mary]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://law.wm.edu/ William and Mary Law School]\n{{The College of William & Mary}}\n{{Law Schools of the Mid-Atlantic States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:William and Mary}}\n[[Category:Law schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary schools and programs|Law]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1770s]]\n[[Category:1779 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_%26_Mary_Law_School"}
{"title_page": "Washington and Lee University School of Law", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=March 2018}}\n{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n}}\n{{Coord|37|47|29.2|N|79|26|37.9|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox law school\n|name           = Washington and Lee University School of Law\n|image          = W&L law logo.jpg\n|image_size     = 150px\n|motto          = ''[[Non incautus futuri]]'' <small>([[Latin]])</small>\n|mottoeng       = \"Not Unmindful of the Future\"\n|established    = 1849 by [[John White Brockenbrough]]<br>1866 (merger with [[Washington and Lee University|Washington College]])\n|type           = [[Private school|Private]] [[Law school in the United States|school of law]]\n|endowment      = US $85.7 million (2013)<ref name=\"Washington and Lee School of Law Magazine, Winter 2014\">{{cite web|title=http://www.wlulawmag-digital.com/|url=http://www.wlulawmag-digital.com/wlulawmag/winter_2014#pg4|publisher=www.wlulawmag-digital.com|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n|dean           = Brant J. Hellwig\n|city           = [[Lexington, Virginia|Lexington]]\n|state          = [[Virginia]]\n|country        = [[United States|USA]]\n|academic_staff = 40<ref name=\"Meet Our Faculty : Washington and Lee University\">{{cite web|title=https://law.wlu.edu/faculty|url=https://law.wlu.edu/faculty|publisher=law.wlu.com|accessdate=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n|students       = 383<ref name=\"W&L Quick Facts\">{{cite web|title=J.D. Quick Facts|url=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/jd-quick-facts|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n|campus         = [[National Register of Historic Places|National Historic Landmark]], [[Rural area|Rural]], {{convert|325|acre|km2}}\n|former_names   = Lexington Law School (1849-1866)<br>\nSchool of Law and Equity (1866-1870)<br />\n|ranking        = 31st (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington and Lee University School of Law |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/washington-and-lee-university-03163 |website=Best Law Schools \u2013 U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|nickname       = \"The Generals\"\n|colors         = [[Royal Blue]] and [[White]]<BR>{{color box|#002366}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n|website        = [http://law.wlu.edu/ law.wlu.edu]\n|logo           = \n}}\nThe '''Washington and Lee University School of Law''' ('''W&L Law''') is a private  [[American Bar Association]]-accredited [[law school]] located in [[Lexington, Virginia|Lexington]] in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] region of [[Virginia]]. Facilities are on the historic campus of [[Washington and Lee University]] in [[Sydney Lewis|Sydney Lewis Hall]]. W&L Law has a total enrollment of approximately 365 students in the [[Juris Doctor]] program and a 6-to-1 student to faculty ratio.\n\n==History==\nThe Lexington Law School, the precursor to W&L Law, was founded in 1849 by [[United States federal judge]] [[John White Brockenbrough]] and is the [[Law school in the United States#Oldest active law schools|16th oldest active law school]] in the United States and the third-oldest in Virginia. The Law School was not integrated into Washington and Lee University (then known as Washington College) until after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] when [[Robert E. Lee]] was [[List of Presidents of Washington and Lee University|president]] of the university. In 1866, General Lee annexed the school, known at the time as the School of Law and Equity, to the college and appointed Judge Brockenbrough as the first dean. In 1870, after Lee's death, the School of Law and Equity was renamed as the Washington and Lee University School of Law, in line with the college's name change in honor of General Lee. Also in 1870, former Virginia Attorney General [[John Randolph Tucker (1823\u20131897)|John Randolph Tucker]] was appointed to the faculty and later became Dean followed by his son [[Henry St. George Tucker, Sr.]] In 1900, the law school moved into the newly built Tucker Hall in memory of Dean Tucker. Tucker Hall also housed the law school's first law library\u2014the Vincent L. Bradford Law Library. After significant periods of growth, the law school moved into new Tucker Hall after the original building was destroyed in a fire and the law library was rebuilt with a grant from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]]. In 1920, W&L Law joined the [[Association of American Law Schools]]. The ''[[Washington and Lee Law Review]]'' began publication in the Autumn of 1939 and is still in regular publication. After [[World War II]], enrollment increased despite a period of low enrollment during the war. In 1950, the School of Law established its chapter of the [[Order of the Coif]], one of only 80 such chapters in the country. The School of Law admitted its first female students in 1972, and opened its current home, Sydney Lewis Hall, in 1977. In 1992, the [[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.|Lewis F. Powell, Jr. Wing]] was added to Sydney Lewis Hall and the Wilbur C. Hall Law Library at a dedication ceremony attended by Justice Powell and presided over by Chief Justice [[William Rehnquist]]. In 2008, Dean [[Rodney Smolla]] announced the new third-year program, which became compulsory for W&L Law students in 2011 under Interim Dean Mark Grunewald. This new program turned the entire third year into an experiential curriculum which emphasizes practice, professionalism, and service. [[Nora Demleitner]] served as Dean from 2012 through 2015, the only woman to hold the position, during which time the school completed its $35 million campaign, ''Honor Our Past, Build Our Future'',<ref>{{cite web|title=A Successful Conclusion to the Capital Campaign |url=http://alumni.blogs.wlu.edu/a-successful-conclusion-to-the-capital-campaign/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-09-25}}</ref> renovated Lewis Hall, established the Washington, DC portion of W&L's third-year program,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law2.wlu.edu/externships/page.asp?pageid=1684|title=DC Program : Externship Program |website=wlu.edu |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> and significantly increased the employment<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Releases New Employment Report |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/04/14/wl-law-releases-new-employment-report/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-09-25}}</ref> and bar passage<ref>{{cite web|title=http://barexam.virginia.gov/bar/barresults.html}}</ref> rates of its graduates. On July 1, 2015, Brant J. Hellwig became Dean of the law school, the 18th Dean since 1849.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/02/25/brant-hellwig-named-next-dean-of-wl-law/|title=Brant Hellwig Named Next Dean of W&L Law|publisher=Washington and Lee University|first=Peter|last=Jetton|work=wlu.edu|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, W&L Law formed an academic and professional partnership with the [[Future of Privacy Forum]], an information privacy think tank in [[Washington, DC]]. The Future of Privacy Forum will facilitate professional, research, and curricular development and the Washington, DC portion of W&L's third-year program will move into its offices.<ref>{{cite web|title=DC-Based Privacy Think Tank Future of Privacy Forum Partners with W&L Law |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/10/29/dc-based-privacy-think-tank-future-of-privacy-forum-partners-with-wl-law/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Slh.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Sydney Lewis Hall|Sydney Lewis Hall]]\nSydney Lewis Hall is the home of the school of law on the [[Washington and Lee University Historic District|historic campus]] of Washington and Lee in Lexington, Virginia. Lewis Hall was built in 1977 with a $9 million gift from [[Best Products]] founder [[Sydney Lewis]] and his wife Frances of Virginia. Lewis Hall was designed by Marcellus Wright Cox & Smith Architects in the [[Mid-century modern]] style.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://bcwh.com/wl-library-renovation/}}</ref> In addition to lecture halls, classrooms, and offices for faculty and staff, Lewis Hall houses the 150-seat Millhiser Moot Courtroom with the accompanying Robert E. Stroud Judge's Chambers and the Roger D. Groot Jury Room. The Millhiser Moot Courtroom serves as the continuity of operations site for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2016/03/07/u-s-appeals-court-for-the-federal-circuit-to-hear-cases-at-wl-law/| publisher=Washington and Lee University |title=U.S. Appeals Court for the Federal Circuit to Hear Cases at W&L Law|accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref> Lewis Hall also has a cafeteria for students, staff, and faculty called the Brief Stop, which serves food, snacks, and drinks. As part of its recently completed $35 million campaign, ''Honor Our Past, Build Our Future'', the School of Law began an $8 million renovation and modernization project in the summer of 2014 and completed in the summer of 2015. The project resulted in more flexible space for student collaboration and study, new homes for four of the school's legal clinics and student organizations, more natural lighting, a new library reading room, a new high-tech trial courtroom, and an improved entry sequence and navigation for the building.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2014/06/23/wl-law-building-renovation-to-commence-summer-2014/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=http://law.wlu.edu/deptimages/law%20news/LawNewsVol41No3.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=http://bcwh.com/work/washington-lee-law-library/}}</ref>\n\nLewis Hall's cornerstones are the Wilbur C. Hall Law Library and Lewis F. Powell, Jr. Wing. The {{convert|58155|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Wilbur C. Hall Law Library is a [[Federal Depository Library Program|Federal Depository Library for the U.S. Government]] and includes a separate faculty library, a rare book room, and an audio-visual media center and is open 24-hours a day. The library houses more than 492,000 volumes and is unique in offering each student personally designated work and storage space. The Powell Wing was built in 1992 to house the professional and personal papers and archives of the [[United States Supreme Court Justice]] and noted W&L alum as well as other manuscript collections, rare books, and archives of the law school.<ref>{{cite web|title=law.wlu.edu/powellarchives|url=http://law.wlu.edu/powellarchives/|accessdate=2012-12-17}}</ref> The Powell Wing includes an expanded main reading room space, in addition to stack area and work space for the papers. The archives are managed by full-time staff and are open to researchers, faculty, and students.\n\n==Programs and admissions==\nW&L Law's full-time [[Juris Doctor]] program, one of the smallest in the country, is the primary degree-program at the Law School. The Class of 2021 numbered 131 students with a median [[Law School Admission Test|LSAT]] of 163 and a median undergraduate [[Academic grading in the United States|grade point average]] of 3.50.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/class-of-2021-profile|title=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/class-of-2021-profile|accessdate=2018-04-03}}</ref>  International exchange programs are available for Juris Doctor students with [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]] in [[Dublin, Ireland|Dublin]] and the [[University of Copenhagen]] in [[Copenhagen, Denmark|Copenhagen]].\n\n==Rankings and reputation==\nWashington and Lee University School of Law ranked 31st out of 198 in the 2021 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' national ranking of America's law schools.<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite web|title=Best Law Schools|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+2}}</ref> Since the ''U.S. News'' rankings of law schools were first released in 1987, W&L Law has had an average ranking of 26th nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-law handbook-Law school rankings 1987-1999|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__1987_1999|publisher=prelawhandbook.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-law handbook-Law school rankings 2000-Present|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__2000_present|publisher=prelawhandbook.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US News Rankings: A Chart of the Past Decade|url=http://www.concurringopinions.com/archives/2006/04/us_news_ranking_1.html|publisher=concurringopinions.com|accessdate=2013-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 2013 Law School Rankings|url=http://www.top-law-schools.com/rankings.html|publisher=top-law-schools.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref> [[Brian Leiter]] ranked W&L Law's endowment-per-student as 14th in the country, at $214,000 per student, when adjusted for cost-of-living.<ref>{{cite web|title=leiterlawschool.typepad.com|url=http://leiterlawschool.typepad.com/leiter/2006/09/top_20_law_scho.html|publisher=leiterlawschool.typepad.com|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> [[Above the Law (blog)|Above the Law]] ranked W&L Law 22nd nationally in their 2019 Top 50 Law Schools rankings<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2019 ATL Top 50 Law School Rankings|url=https://abovethelaw.com/law-school-rankings/top-law-schools-2019/}}</ref> and, in 2017, 4th nationally in their rankings for the top-rated law schools when measuring alumni satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|title=ATL Law School Rankings: Top Schools By Category|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/06/atl-law-school-rankings-top-schools-by-category/|publisher=abovethelaw.com|accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref> ''National Jurist'' ranked W&L Law 15th in its list of best law schools for standard of living and 18th in its ranking of the best law libraries.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.nationaljurist.com|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-law-schools-standard-living|accessdate=2011-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=www.nationaljurist.com|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-law-libraries|accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The 2013 edition of ''On Being a Black Lawyer: The Black Student's Guide to Law Schools'', ranked W&L Law 25th in its rankings of the best law schools for black law students.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.onbeingablacklawyer.com|url=http://www.onbeingablacklawyer.com/obabl/schools1/index.html#/14/zoomed|accessdate=2012-10-18}}</ref> In 2013, ''National Jurist'' named W&L's law faculty as the 10th most influential in legal education (the only entire faculty on the list)<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, January 2013|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0113/index.php#/0|accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and 18th in 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, January 2014|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0114/#/14|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> as well as awarding W&L Law's practical training program a B+ grade in its 2014 listing of the best law schools for practical training.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, March 2014|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0314/#/24|accessdate=2014-03-12}}</ref> ''National Jurist'' also ranked W&L Law as the 5th best value private law school in 2016 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, December 2016|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist_2016fall/#/10|accessdate=2016-12-03}}</ref> A ranking of scholarly impact published in the ''[[University of St. Thomas School of Law|University of St. Thomas Law Journal]]'' ranked the faculty 30th nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=TaxProf Blog|url=http://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2013/08/the-71.html|accessdate=2013-08-19}}</ref> A 2015 ranking by [[Business Insider]], listed W&L Law as the 17th best law schools in the United States to make connections and get a job.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 best law schools in the US to make connections and get a job|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/best-law-schools-for-networking-in-the-us-2015-6}}</ref> Washington and Lee's ''The Law News'' has been awarded the ABA's award of the finest law school student newspaper four times, including three years in a row, in 1985, 2013, 2014, and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Student Newspaper wins top ABA Award for Second Straight Year|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2014/10/20/wl-law-student-newspaper-wins-top-aba-award-for-second-straight-year/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Student Newspaper Wins Top ABA Award for Third Straight Year|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/09/02/wl-law-student-newspaper-wins-top-aba-award-for-third-straight-year/}}</ref> In 2016, ''National Jurist'' included W&L Law on its list of one of the twelve best value private law schools in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, August 2016|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-value-law-schools-2016|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Bar exam results==\nW&L's Virginia [[Admission to the bar in the United States|bar]] passage rate on the July 2017 exam was 86.67% (the state average was 76.43%); W&L had the highest combined average passage rate among Virginia schools for the July 2014 and 2015 exams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barexam.virginia.gov/bar/barresults.html|accessdate=2015-10-30|title=VBBE - Bar Exam - Results}}</ref>  W&L's [[New York (state)|New York]] bar passage rate on the July 2015 exam was 92.86% (the state average for ABA law school graduates was 79%). Nationally, W&L Class of 2014 graduates had a 90% passage rate on bar exams in all states.<ref>{{cite web|title=ABA Required Disclosures|url=http://law.wlu.edu/about-wandl-law/aba-required-disclosures|accessdate=2015-02-10}}</ref> W&L Law was ranked as having the 20th best bar passage rate nationally based on Class of 2015 data.<ref>{{cite web|title=Law schools with highest bar pass rates|url=http://wtop.com/education/2016/05/law-schools-highest-bar-pass-rates/|accessdate=2016-05-31|date=2016-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Post-graduation employment==\nBased on Class of 2015 data, 85% of W&L Law graduates obtained full-time, long term JD-required or preferred jobs within 10 months of graduation. 50% of the 2015 graduates obtained full-time long-term jobs in law firms (including 21% of graduates getting full-time, long term jobs in firms greater than 100 lawyers) and 19% of 2015 graduates obtained clerkships.<ref>{{cite web|title=EMPLOYMENT SUMMARY FOR 2015 GRADUATES|url=http://law2.wlu.edu/admissions/nalp/ABAEmploymentSummary2016.pdf|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2016-05-28}}</ref> The large law firms which employed the most W&L Law graduates were [[Hunton & Williams]], [[Alston & Bird]], [[McGuireWoods]], [[K&L Gates]], and [[King & Spalding]].<ref>{{cite web|title=www.abovethelaw.com|url=http://abovethelaw.com/schools/washington-lee-law-school/|publisher=www.abovethelaw.com|accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The School of Law ranked 18th on the 2012 ''U.S. News''' ranking of law schools by recruiters from the top national law firms<ref>{{cite web|title=www.usnews.com|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/articles/2011/03/07/law-firm-recruiters-rank-best-law-schools|publisher=www.usnews.com|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> and 19th on the 2015 ''U.S News'' ranking of law schools that send the most students to clerk for a [[United States federal judge]] (6.9%).<ref>{{cite web|title=https://www.usnews.com/education/blogs/college-rankings-blog/2014/06/12/grads-of-these-law-schools-get-the-most-judicial-clerkships|publisher=www.usnews.com}}</ref> The ''[[National Law Journal]]'' ranked W&L Law 33rd in its 2015 \"Go-To Law Schools\" list of law schools that send the highest percentage of students to the 250 largest law firms in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://www.nationallawjournal.com/id=1202718517845/The-Top-50-GoTo-Schools?mcode=1202619327776&curindex=0}}</ref>\n\n==Juris Doctor curriculum==\nThe Juris Doctor curriculum at W&L consists three unique and integrated years of full-time study with a mix of traditional [[casebook method]] and practice-oriented courses.\n\n;First-year\n\nIn the 1L year, students take required foundational courses in [[contract law]], [[tort law]], [[Civil procedure in the United States|civil procedure]], [[criminal law]], [[property law]], [[professional responsibility]], [[United States administrative law|administrative law]], and [[international law]]. Additionally, each student is assigned a small section in which one substantive required course also serves as a [[legal writing]] course. This small section consists of approximately 20 students. 1Ls are also assigned to an upper-level student from the Burks Scholar Program who teaches [[legal research]] and [[Bluebook]] methods.\n\n;Second-year\n\nIn the 2L year, students focus on advanced coursework. W&L requires [[evidence law]] and [[United States Constitution|constitutional law]] in the second-year as well as the completion of an upper-level writing requirement. The writing requirement can be satisfied through a seminar course, through an independent writing project, or a note in one of the law journals. All other courses in the 2L year are electives and commonly include [[corporate law]] and [[Taxation in the United States|tax law]] as well as many other classes and seminars. Since establishing the practice-based curriculum, W&L incorporated its experiential curricular offerings, such as practicum courses, into the second-year in addition to casebook-oriented electives.\n\n;Third-year\n\nThe new third-year program, which began in the fall of 2010, replaced further elective advanced coursework based on the casebook method as is the norm in most [[American Bar Association|ABA]] law schools. Instead, the program is meant to  simulate client experiences. The 3L year requires students to exercise professional judgment, work in teams, solve problems, counsel clients, negotiate solutions, serve as advocates and counselors \u2014 the full complement of professional activity that engages practicing lawyers as they apply legal theory and doctrines to the real-world issues of serving clients ethically and honorably within the highest traditions of the profession.\n\nThe Fall semester begins with an immersion course. Students are allowed to choose one of two courses for the two-week immersion. Immersion focuses on either [[litigation]] and [[alternative dispute resolution]] or transactional practice. Each student is then enrolled in practicum courses of their choosing. These courses cover substantive and advanced law but do so through practical methods of drafting paperwork and problem-solving rather than casebook and the [[socratic method]]. Students are also required to take a course in the [[legal profession]] as well as a law-related service requirement. Finally, each student is required to be involved in one of W&L's legal clinics, externship programs, or transnational programs to gain real-client experience. The program is flexible and allows students the ability to tailor their schedule and, if they wish, to take several traditional casebook method courses.\n\n==The Honor System==\nThe [[Honor system|Honor System]] has been run by the student body since 1905 and is derived from Robert E. Lee during his tenure as [[List of Presidents of Washington and Lee University|President]] of the University. Any student found guilty of an Honor Violation by his or her peers is subject to a single penalty: expulsion. The Honor System is defined and administered solely by students, and there is no higher review. A formal review, occasionally including referenda, is held every three years to refine the tenets of the Honor System. Students continue to support the Honor System and its single penalty overwhelmingly, and alumni regularly point to the Honor System as one of the distinctive marks they carry with them from their W&L experience. W&L Law students enjoy several distinct benefits from the Honor System. These include more freedom in exam taking as well as an informal account system at the Brief Stop cafeteria in Sydney Lewis Hall. These are balanced by the strict penalty of a violation of the Honor System.\n\nStudents pledge the following prior to turning in assignments and exams:\n\n\"On my honor, I have neither given nor received any unacknowledged aid on this (exam, test, paper, etc.).\"\n\n==Clinics, journals, moot court, and centers==\n[[File:W&LLawLib.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Wilbur C. Hall Law Library|Wilbur C. Hall Law Library]]\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School houses six clinics:\n* Advanced Administrative Litigation Clinic (Black Lung)\n* Practice Clinic\n* Criminal Justice Clinic\n* Immigrant Rights Clinic\n* Tax Clinic\n* Virginia Capital Case Clearinghouse\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School is home to the following centers:\n* Center for Law and History\n* Frances Lewis Law Center\n* Transnational Law Institute\n* The Law School is also a major partner in the [[Roger Mudd|Mudd Center for Ethics]]\n|}\n\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School offers five moot court programs:\n* Client Counseling Competition\n* The John W. Davis Appellate Advocacy Competition\n* Mock Trial Competition\n* The Robert J. Grey Jr. Negotiations Competition\n* Representation in Mediation Competition\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School is host to three academic journals:\n* ''[[German Law Journal]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.germanlawjournal.com/|title=HOME|website=GERMAN LAW JOURNAL|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref>\n* ''[http://law.wlu.edu/crsj/ Journal of Civil Rights and Social Justice]''\n* ''[[Washington and Lee Law Review]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lawreview.journals.wlu.io/|title=Washington and Lee Law Review|website=lawreview.journals.wlu.io|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notable alumni==\nW&L Law has produced many notable graduates in Virginia, and at the national and global level. Included amongst the alumni ranks are two [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court|Justices of the United States Supreme Court]], seven [[List of Presidents of the American Bar Association|Presidents]] of the [[American Bar Association]], two [[Solicitor General of the United States|Solicitors General of the United States]], one major party candidate for [[President of the United States]], [[Cabinet of the United States|Presidential Cabinet]] members, as well as numerous state governors, United States Congressmen, United States Senators, federal and state judges, influential academics, business leaders, and distinguished attorneys. The list below is not exhaustive. The date following the name is the Law School class. Alumni with two dates also attended as undergraduates and the order is alphabetical.\n\n[[File:Newton Baker, Bain bw photo portrait.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Newton D. Baker]], Class of 1894, [[United States Secretary of War]]]]\n[[File:Terry Brooks.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Terry Brooks]], Class of 1969, [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Best Selling Author]]]]\n[[File:John William Davis.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John W. Davis]], Class of 1892, [[United States Solicitor General]]]]\n[[File:John Goode - Brady-Handy.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John Goode]], [[United States Solicitor General]]]]\n[[File:Rep Bob Goodlatte.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Bob Goodlatte]], Class of 1977, Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]]]\n[[File:Joseph Lamar.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Joseph Rucker Lamar]], Class of 1878, [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court]]]]\n[[File:Marsh, John O 2.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John Otho Marsh, Jr.]], Class of 1951, [[United States Secretary of the Army]]]]\n[[File:US Supreme Court Justice Lewis Powell - 1976 official portrait.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.]], Class of 1931, [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court]]]]\n'''Academia'''\n*[[Rona