essdate=27 March 2015|date=2013-04-24}}</ref>\n*[[Gordon P. Robertson]] - CEO of the [[Christian Broadcasting Network]]\n\n'''Government and politics'''\n\n*[[Samuel B. Avis]] - [[United States Congressman]] from [[West Virginia]] from 1913 to 1915\n*[[Robert D. Bailey, Jr.]] - [[West Virginia Secretary of State]] from 1965 to 1969\n*[[Newton D. Baker]] 1894 \u2014 [[Secretary of War]] under President [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[List of mayors of Cleveland|Mayor of Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Newton D. Baker|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/535/000113196/|publisher=NNDB Soylent Communications|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> and named partner at [[BakerHostetler]]\n*[[Franklin Brockson]] - United States Congressman from [[Delaware]] from 1913 to 1915\n*[[Clarence J. Brown]] 1915 - President of [[Brown Publishing Company]] and US Congressman from Ohio from 1939 to 1965\n*[[Nathan P. Bryan]] 1895 - US Senator from the State of Florida, Judge on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Nathan P. Bryan|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000992|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[William James Bryan]] 1899 - US Senator from Florida<ref>{{cite web|title=William James Bryan|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000994|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Bruce L. Castor, Jr.]] 1986 \u2014 Attorney General (interim) and Solicitor General of Pennsylvania; District Attorney, [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]] (2000\u20132008); Commissioner, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania (2008-2016 ); President Pennsylvania District Attorneys' Association<ref>{{cite web|title=Bruce L. Castor, Jr.|url=http://www2.montcopa.org/montco/cwp/view,a,3,q,87046.asp|publisher=County of Montgomery, PA|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Edward Cooper (congressman)|Edward Cooper]] - US Congressman from West Virginia from 1915 to 1919\n*[[Spencer Cox (politician)|Spencer Cox]] 2001 - [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Cox|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2013/10/09/wl-law-alum-named-utahs-lieutenant-governor/|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n*[[William Fadjo Cravens]] - US Congressman from Arkansas\n*[[John J. Davis (congressman)|John J. Davis]] 1856 - [[United States Representative]] from [[West Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John J. Davis|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000119|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[John W. Davis]] 1895, 1892 \u2014 1924 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[United States President]]; Ambassador to [[United Kingdom|Britain]]; [[United States Solicitor General|Solicitor General]]; argued more cases before the Supreme Court than anyone else in the twentieth century; [[American Bar Association]] President; first President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]; and named partner at [[Davis Polk & Wardwell]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John W. Davis|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000121|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Joe Donnelly]] 1981- United States Senator from [[Indiana]]<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Alums Win Elections in Virginia, Indiana|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2012/11/07/wl-law-alums-win-elections-in-virginia-indiana/|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[John P. Fishwick, Jr.]], former [[United States Attorney]] for the [[Western District of Virginia]]. Attorney in private practice in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n*[[Vance A. Funk, III]] 1968 - [[Mayor]] of [[Newark, Delaware]]\n*[[John Goode]] - 3rd [[Solicitor General of the United States]] and [[United States Congressman]] from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=John Goode|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000277|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Bob Goodlatte]] 1977 - United States Congressman from Virginia and Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Bob Goodlatte|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=g000289|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[R. Booth Goodwin]] 1996 - [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of West Virginia|Southern District of West Virginia]]\n*[[Morgan Griffith]] 1983 - Congressman from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Morgan Griffith|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000568|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[http://perb.dc.gov/biography/ondray-t-harris Ondray T. Harris] - Executive director of the Public Employee Relations Board of the [[District of Columbia]]\n*[[James Hay (politician)|James Hay]] 1877 - [[United States Representative]] from Virginia and Federal Judge on the [[United States Court of Claims]]<ref>{{cite web|title=James Hay|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H000382|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[George Washington Hays]] - [[Governor of Arkansas]] from 1913 to 1917\n*[[Homer A. Holt]] 1918, 1923 - [[Governor of West Virginia]] from 1937 to 1941<ref name=\"Homer A. Holt\">{{cite web|title=Homer A. Holt|url=http://www.wvculture.org/history/homeholt.html|publisher=West Virginia State Archives|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[James Murray Hooker]] 1896 - US Congressman from Virginia\n*[[James L. Kemper]] - 1842, Governor of Virginia, Confederate General Leading Pickett's Charge<ref>{{cite web|title=James L. Kemper|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_virginia/col2-content/main-content-list/title_kemper_james.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Ruby Laffoon]] 1890 - Governor of Kentucky <ref>{{cite web|title=Ruby Laffoon|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_kentucky/col2-content/main-content-list/title_laffoon_ruby.html|publisher=National Governors Association|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Edwin Gray Lee]] 1859 - [[Brigadier General]] in the [[Confederate States of America]]\n*[[Scott Marion Loftin]] 1899 - US Senator from Florida and President of the [[American Bar Association]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Scott Marion Loftin|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=L000400|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Mary Beth Long]] 1998 - Former [[Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs]] at the [[United States Department of Defense]] and former attorney with [[Williams & Connolly LLP]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n*[[John Otho Marsh, Jr.]] 1951 - [[Secretary of the Army]], 1981\u20131989, United States Congressman<ref>{{cite web|title=John Otho Marsh, Jr|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000148|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Henry M. Mathews]] 1857 - [[Governor of West Virginia]]<ref name=Addkison>\nAddkison-Simmons, D. (2010). Henry Mason Mathews. ''e-WV: The West Virginia Encyclopedia''. Retrieved December 11, 2012, from http://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/1582</ref>\n*[[Robert Murphy Mayo]] 1859 - [[United States Representative]] from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Murphy Mayo|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000287|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas Chipman McRae]] - Governor of Arkansas, United States Representative<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Chipman McRae|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000597|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Mark Obenshain]] 1987 - Member of the [[Senate of Virginia]] and Republican nominee for [[Attorney General of Virginia]] in the [[Virginia elections, 2013|2013 Virginia election]]\n*[[Mark J. Peake]] 1988 - Member of the [[Senate of Virginia]] \n*[[Miles Poindexter]] 1891 - Senator from the State of Washington <ref>{{cite web|title=Miles Poindexter|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000403|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Lacey E. Putney]] \u2014 Longest serving member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] in the history of the [[Virginia General Assembly]]<ref>{{cite web|title=House Joint Resolution No. 203|url=https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?121+ful+HJ203+pdf|website=lis.virginia.gov|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Heartsill Ragon]] - US Congressman from Arkansas and federal judge on the United States District Court for the Western District of Arkansas\n*[[Robert W. Ray]] 1985 - Partner at [[Fox Rothschild]] in New York City and former head of the US [[Office of the Independent Counsel]] (succeeded [[Kenneth Starr]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert W. Ray|url=http://pryorcashman.com}}</ref> \n*[[Alfred E. Reames]] 1893 \u2014 US Senator from [[Oregon]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Alfred E. Reames|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000099|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Tom Sansonetti]] 1976 - [[United States Assistant Attorney General]] for the [[United States Department of Justice Environment and Natural Resources Division]]\n*