zbach]] 1896 - US Congressman from [[Texas]]\n\n'''Judiciary'''\n*[[William T. Brotherton, Jr.]] - Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of West Virginia]] from 1989 to 1994\n*[[Archibald C. Buchanan]] 1914 - Justice on the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]]\n*[[Christian Compton]] 1950, 1953 - Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]] from 1974 to 2006<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://law2.wlu.edu/powellarchives/page.asp?pageid=281|title=Powell News archive :: Powell Archives :: W&L Law School|website=law2.wlu.edu|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n*[[Mark Steven Davis]] 1988 - United States District Court Judge for the [[Eastern District of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Steven Davis|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=3175&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[John W. Eggleston]] 1910 - Chief Justice of the Virginia Supreme Court from 1958 to 1969\n*[[Herbert B. Gregory]] 1911 - Justice on the Virginia Supreme Court from 1930 to 1951\n*[[Duncan Lawrence Groner]] 1894 - US Attorney, Federal District Judge for [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia]], Chief Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Duncan Lawrence Groner|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=921&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Alexander M. Harman, Jr.]] - Justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia from 1969 to 1979\n*[[Jerrauld Jones]] 1980 - Judge on the Norfolk Circuit Court\n*[[Walter Kelley]] 1977, 1981 - Former [[federal judge]] in the [[Eastern District of Virginia]] and current partner at [[Jones Day]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter Kelley|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=3069&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Jackson L. Kiser]] 1952 - Judge on the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]]\n*[[Joseph Rucker Lamar]] 1878 \u2014 [[Associate Justice|Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]] of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] (1911\u20131916), Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Georgia (U.S. state)|Supreme Court of Georgia]] (1903-1905)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/justices/joseph_r_lamar|title=Joseph R. Lamar|website=Oyez|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n*[[Harry Jacob Lemley]] 1910 - Federal Judge on both the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Arkansas]] and the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Arkansas]]\n*[[Daniel B. Lucas]] - Poet and justice on the Supreme Court of West Virginia from 1889 to 1892\n*[[John Ashton MacKenzie]] 1939 - Federal Judge for the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=John Ashton MacKenzie|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1454&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Charles W. Mason]] 1911 - Justice of the Oklahoma Supreme Court 1923 - 1931\n*[[Robert E. Payne]] 1967 - Judge for the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert E. Payne|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=1855&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Lewis Franklin Powell, Jr.]] 1929, 1931 \u2014 Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court (1972\u20131987), President of the American Bar Association, and named partner at [[Hunton & Williams|Hunton Williams Gay Powell & Gibson]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Lewis Franklin Powell, Jr|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/749/000117398/|publisher=NNDB Soylent Communications|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[William Ray Price, Jr.]] 1978 - Longest serving judge and former Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Missouri]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William Ray Price, Jr|url=http://www.courts.mo.gov/page.jsp?id=1813|publisher=Your Missouri Courts|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Daniel K. Sadler]] - Justice on the [[New Mexico Supreme Court]]\n*[[Roscoe B. Stephenson, Jr.]] 1943, 1947 - Justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia\n*[[James Clinton Turk]] 1952 -  Federal judge and Chief Judge (1973 to 1993) on the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]] \n*[[Sol Wachtler]] - former [[Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals]] (1985\u20131993)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nycourts.gov/history/legal-history-new-york/oral-histories/oral-histories-wachtler.html|title=Historical Society of the New York Courts {{!}} New York Legal History / Oral Histories|website=www.nycourts.gov|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n*[[Kennon C. Whittle]] 1914 - Justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia and President of the [[Virginia Bar Association]]\n*[[H. Emory Widener, Jr.]] 1953 - Judge for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]<ref name=\"H. Emory Widener, Jr\">{{cite web|title=H. Emory Widener, Jr|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2574&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Biographical Directory of Federal Judges|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Private attorneys'''\n*[[Robert J. Grey, Jr.]] 1976 - American Bar Association President 2004\u20132005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hunton.com/Robert_Grey/|title=Robert J. Grey Jr. {{!}} Professionals {{!}} Hunton & Williams LLP|website=www.hunton.com|access-date=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n*[[Linda Klein (lawyer)|Linda A. Klein]] 1983 - Immediate past president of the American Bar Association, former chair of the ABA House of Delegates, managing partner of the Georgia offices of [[Baker, Donelson, Bearman, Caldwell & Berkowitz]]<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Alumna Linda Klein '83L Named President of the American Bar Association|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2016/08/09/wl-alumna-linda-klein-83l-named-president-of-the-american-bar-association/|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref> \n*[[Morgan Meyer]] 1999 - Lawyer for [[Bracewell & Giuliani]] in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], and incoming 2015 Republican member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bracewellgiuliani.com/people/morgan-d-meyer|title=Morgan D. Meyer|publisher=bracewellgiuliani.com|accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Prescott Prince]] 1983 \u2014 Attorney defending [[Khalid Sheikh Mohammed]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n*[[Christopher Wolf]] 1980 - Partner at [[Hogan Lovells]], widely recognized as one of the leading American practitioners in the field of [[Information privacy law|privacy]] and data security law, and founder and co-chair of the [[Future of Privacy Forum]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Notable faculty==\n[[File:Henry St. George Tucker III 2.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Henry St. George Tucker III]], Class of 1879, [[United States Representative]] from [[Virginia]]]]\n[[File:Judge Headshot edited-1.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Hiram Emory Widener, Jr.|H. Emory Widener, Jr.]], Class of 1953, [[United States federal judge|Senior Judge]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]]]\n*[[John White Brockenbrough]] - Federal Judge, founder, and former Dean of the Washington and Lee University School of Law\n*[[Martin P. Burks]] - Former Dean and justice on the [[Virginia Supreme Court]]\n*[[David Bruck]] - Noted capital defense attorney, Supreme Court advocate, and Director of the Virginia Capital Clearinghouse at W&L Law\n*[[Judy Clarke]] - Noted criminal defense attorney for [[Ted Kaczynski]], [[Zacarias Moussaoui]], [[Susan Smith]], [[Eric Rudolph]], [[Jared Lee Loughner]], and [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev]]\n*[[John W. Davis]] 1895, 1892 - 1924 Democratic nominee for U.S. President; [[United States Solicitor General]]; and [[American Bar Association]] President\n*[[Creigh Deeds]] - Democratic nominee for [[Governor of Virginia]] in 2009 and [[Senate of Virginia|Virginia State Senator]]\n*[[Nora Demleitner]] - Former Dean of W&L Law and [[Hofstra University School of Law]]\n*[http://ualr.edu/law/john-dipippa/ John DiPippa] 1978 \u2014 former Dean of the [[University of Arkansas at Little Rock School of Law]]\n*[[Charles A. Graves]] 1872 - Professor at W&L Law and at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]]\n*[[Roger Groot]] - Professor of Criminal Law and noted death penalty expert\n*[[Homer A. Holt]] 1918, 1923 - [[Governor of West Virginia]] from 1937 to 1941<ref name=\"Homer A. Holt\"/> \n*[[Robert Huntley]] 1950, 1957 - Former Dean of W&L Law, former President of Washington and Lee University, former President, Chairman, and CEO of [[Best Products]]\n*[[Allan Ides]] - Professor and [[Constitutional Law]] and [[Civil Procedure]] expert\n*[[Timothy Jost]] - Professor and expert in [[health law]]\n*[[Donald W. Lemons]] - Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia]]\n*[[Jeffrey P. Minear]] - Counselor to Chief Justice [[John G. Roberts, Jr.]]\n*[[Blake Morant]] - Dean of the [[George Washington Law School]] and former Dean of the [[Wake Forest University School of Law]]\n*[http://www.law.emory.edu/faculty/faculty-profiles/david-f-partlett.html David F. Partlett] - Former Dean of W&L Law and of [[Emory University School of Law]]\n*[[Leander J. Shaw, Jr.]] - Chief Justice of the [[Florida Supreme Court]]\n*[[Rodney A. Smolla]] - Dean of [[Widener University]]-Delaware Law, Former Dean of W&L Law and [[University of Richmond School of Law]], First Amendment scholar, and former President of [[Furman University]]\n*[[Abram Penn Staples]] 1908 - [[Attorney General of Virginia]] and justice on the Virginia Supreme Court\n*[[Waller Redd Staples]] - Member of the [[Confederate House of Representatives]] and justice on the Virginia Supreme Court\n*[[Barry Sullivan (lawyer)|Barry Sullivan]] - Former Dean and currently professor at [[Loyola University Chicago School of Law]]\n*[[Henry St. George Tucker III]] 1876 - Former Dean of W&L Law, Dean of the [[George Washington University Law School]], Congressman from Virginia, and former President of the [[American Bar Association]]\n*[[John Randolph Tucker (1823\u20131897)|John Randolph Tucker]] - Virginia Attorney General, former Dean, and former President of the American Bar Association\n*[http://law.wlu.edu/faculty/profiledetail.asp?id=359 William R. Vance] 1869 - Professor at [[Yale Law School]], and Dean of W&L Law, [[George Washington University Law School]], and the [[University of Minnesota Law School]]\n*[[H. Emory Widener, Jr.]] 1953 - Judge for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]<ref name=\"H. Emory Widener, Jr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://law.wlu.edu/ Washington and Lee University School of Law]\n*[http://law.wlu.edu/library/ Wilbur C. Hall Law Libaray]\n\n{{Washington and Lee University|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Law Schools of the Mid-Atlantic States|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Washington And Lee University School Of Law}}\n[[Category:Law schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Washington and Lee University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=March 2018}}\n{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n}}\n{{Coord|37|47|29.2|N|79|26|37.9|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox law school\n|name           = Washington and Lee University School of Law\n|image          = W&L law logo.jpg\n|image_size     = 150px\n|motto          = ''[[Non incautus futuri]]'' <small>([[Latin]])</small>\n|mottoeng       = \"Not Unmindful of the Future\"\n|established    = 1849 by [[John White Brockenbrough]]<br>1866 (merger with [[Washington and Lee University|Washington College]])\n|type           = [[Private school|Private]] [[Law school in the United States|school of law]]\n|endowment      = US $85.7 million (2013)<ref name=\"Washington and Lee School of Law Magazine, Winter 2014\">{{cite web|title=http://www.wlulawmag-digital.com/|url=http://www.wlulawmag-digital.com/wlulawmag/winter_2014#pg4|publisher=www.wlulawmag-digital.com|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n|dean           = Brant J. Hellwig\n|city           = [[Lexington, Virginia|Lexington]]\n|state          = [[Virginia]]\n|country        = [[United States|USA]]\n|academic_staff = 40<ref name=\"Meet Our Faculty : Washington and Lee University\">{{cite web|title=https://law.wlu.edu/faculty|url=https://law.wlu.edu/faculty|publisher=law.wlu.com|accessdate=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n|students       = 383<ref name=\"W&L Quick Facts\">{{cite web|title=J.D. Quick Facts|url=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/jd-quick-facts|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n|campus         = [[National Register of Historic Places|National Historic Landmark]], [[Rural area|Rural]], {{convert|325|acre|km2}}\n|former_names   = Lexington Law School (1849-1866)<br>\nSchool of Law and Equity (1866-1870)<br />\n|ranking        = 31st (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington and Lee University School of Law |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/washington-and-lee-university-03163 |website=Best Law Schools \u2013 U.S. News & World Report |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|nickname       = \"The Generals\"\n|colors         = [[Royal Blue]] and [[White]]<BR>{{color box|#002366}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n|website        = [http://law.wlu.edu/ law.wlu.edu]\n|logo           = \n}}\nThe '''Washington and Lee University School of Law''' ('''W&L Law''') is a private  [[American Bar Association]]-accredited [[law school]] located in [[Lexington, Virginia|Lexington]] in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] region of [[Virginia]]. Facilities are on the historic campus of [[Washington and Lee University]] in [[Sydney Lewis|Sydney Lewis Hall]]. W&L Law has a total enrollment of approximately 365 students in the [[Juris Doctor]] program and a 6-to-1 student to faculty ratio.\n\n==History==\nThe Lexington Law School, the precursor to W&L Law, was founded in 1849 by [[United States federal judge]] [[John White Brockenbrough]] and is the [[Law school in the United States#Oldest active law schools|16th oldest active law school]] in the United States and the third-oldest in Virginia. The Law School was not integrated into Washington and Lee University (then known as Washington College) until after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] when [[Robert E. Lee]] was [[List of Presidents of Washington and Lee University|president]] of the university. In 1866, General Lee annexed the school, known at the time as the School of Law and Equity, to the college and appointed Judge Brockenbrough as the first dean. In 1870, after Lee's death, the School of Law and Equity was renamed as the Washington and Lee University School of Law, in line with the college's name change in honor of General Lee. Also in 1870, former Virginia Attorney General [[John Randolph Tucker (1823\u20131897)|John Randolph Tucker]] was appointed to the faculty and later became Dean followed by his son [[Henry St. George Tucker, Sr.]] In 1900, the law school moved into the newly built Tucker Hall in memory of Dean Tucker. Tucker Hall also housed the law school's first law library\u2014the Vincent L. Bradford Law Library. After significant periods of growth, the law school moved into new Tucker Hall after the original building was destroyed in a fire and the law library was rebuilt with a grant from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]]. In 1920, W&L Law joined the [[Association of American Law Schools]]. The ''[[Washington and Lee Law Review]]'' began publication in the Autumn of 1939 and is still in regular publication. After [[World War II]], enrollment increased despite a period of low enrollment during the war. In 1950, the School of Law established its chapter of the [[Order of the Coif]], one of only 80 such chapters in the country. The School of Law admitted its first female students in 1972, and opened its current home, Sydney Lewis Hall, in 1977. In 1992, the [[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.|Lewis F. Powell, Jr. Wing]] was added to Sydney Lewis Hall and the Wilbur C. Hall Law Library at a dedication ceremony attended by Justice Powell and presided over by Chief Justice [[William Rehnquist]]. In 2008, Dean [[Rodney Smolla]] announced the new third-year program, which became compulsory for W&L Law students in 2011 under Interim Dean Mark Grunewald. This new program turned the entire third year into an experiential curriculum which emphasizes practice, professionalism, and service. [[Nora Demleitner]] served as Dean from 2012 through 2015, the only woman to hold the position, during which time the school completed its $35 million campaign, ''Honor Our Past, Build Our Future'',<ref>{{cite web|title=A Successful Conclusion to the Capital Campaign |url=http://alumni.blogs.wlu.edu/a-successful-conclusion-to-the-capital-campaign/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-09-25}}</ref> renovated Lewis Hall, established the Washington, DC portion of W&L's third-year program,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law2.wlu.edu/externships/page.asp?pageid=1684|title=DC Program : Externship Program |website=wlu.edu |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> and significantly increased the employment<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Releases New Employment Report |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/04/14/wl-law-releases-new-employment-report/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-09-25}}</ref> and bar passage<ref>{{cite web|title=http://barexam.virginia.gov/bar/barresults.html}}</ref> rates of its graduates. On July 1, 2015, Brant J. Hellwig became Dean of the law school, the 18th Dean since 1849.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/02/25/brant-hellwig-named-next-dean-of-wl-law/|title=Brant Hellwig Named Next Dean of W&L Law|publisher=Washington and Lee University|first=Peter|last=Jetton|work=wlu.edu|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, W&L Law formed an academic and professional partnership with the [[Future of Privacy Forum]], an information privacy think tank in [[Washington, DC]]. The Future of Privacy Forum will facilitate professional, research, and curricular development and the Washington, DC portion of W&L's third-year program will move into its offices.<ref>{{cite web|title=DC-Based Privacy Think Tank Future of Privacy Forum Partners with W&L Law |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/10/29/dc-based-privacy-think-tank-future-of-privacy-forum-partners-with-wl-law/|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Slh.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Sydney Lewis Hall|Sydney Lewis Hall]]\nSydney Lewis Hall is the home of the school of law on the [[Washington and Lee University Historic District|historic campus]] of Washington and Lee in Lexington, Virginia. Lewis Hall was built in 1977 with a $9 million gift from [[Best Products]] founder [[Sydney Lewis]] and his wife Frances of Virginia. Lewis Hall was designed by Marcellus Wright Cox & Smith Architects in the [[Mid-century modern]] style.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://bcwh.com/wl-library-renovation/}}</ref> In addition to lecture halls, classrooms, and offices for faculty and staff, Lewis Hall houses the 150-seat Millhiser Moot Courtroom with the accompanying Robert E. Stroud Judge's Chambers and the Roger D. Groot Jury Room. The Millhiser Moot Courtroom serves as the continuity of operations site for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2016/03/07/u-s-appeals-court-for-the-federal-circuit-to-hear-cases-at-wl-law/| publisher=Washington and Lee University |title=U.S. Appeals Court for the Federal Circuit to Hear Cases at W&L Law|accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref> Lewis Hall also has a cafeteria for students, staff, and faculty called the Brief Stop, which serves food, snacks, and drinks. As part of its recently completed $35 million campaign, ''Honor Our Past, Build Our Future'', the School of Law began an $8 million renovation and modernization project in the summer of 2014 and completed in the summer of 2015. The project resulted in more flexible space for student collaboration and study, new homes for four of the school's legal clinics and student organizations, more natural lighting, a new library reading room, a new high-tech trial courtroom, and an improved entry sequence and navigation for the building.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2014/06/23/wl-law-building-renovation-to-commence-summer-2014/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=http://law.wlu.edu/deptimages/law%20news/LawNewsVol41No3.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=http://bcwh.com/work/washington-lee-law-library/}}</ref>\n\nLewis Hall's cornerstones are the Wilbur C. Hall Law Library and Lewis F. Powell, Jr. Wing. The {{convert|58155|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Wilbur C. Hall Law Library is a [[Federal Depository Library Program|Federal Depository Library for the U.S. Government]] and includes a separate faculty library, a rare book room, and an audio-visual media center and is open 24-hours a day. The library houses more than 492,000 volumes and is unique in offering each student personally designated work and storage space. The Powell Wing was built in 1992 to house the professional and personal papers and archives of the [[United States Supreme Court Justice]] and noted W&L alum as well as other manuscript collections, rare books, and archives of the law school.<ref>{{cite web|title=law.wlu.edu/powellarchives|url=http://law.wlu.edu/powellarchives/|accessdate=2012-12-17}}</ref> The Powell Wing includes an expanded main reading room space, in addition to stack area and work space for the papers. The archives are managed by full-time staff and are open to researchers, faculty, and students.\n\n==Programs and admissions==\nW&L Law's full-time [[Juris Doctor]] program, one of the smallest in the country, is the primary degree-program at the Law School. The Class of 2021 numbered 131 students with a median [[Law School Admission Test|LSAT]] of 163 and a median undergraduate [[Academic grading in the United States|grade point average]] of 3.50.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/class-of-2021-profile|title=https://law.wlu.edu/admissions/program-information/jd-program/class-of-2021-profile|accessdate=2018-04-03}}</ref>  International exchange programs are available for Juris Doctor students with [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]] in [[Dublin, Ireland|Dublin]] and the [[University of Copenhagen]] in [[Copenhagen, Denmark|Copenhagen]].\n\n==Rankings and reputation==\nWashington and Lee University School of Law ranked 31st out of 198 in the 2021 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' national ranking of America's law schools.<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite web|title=Best Law Schools|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+2}}</ref> Since the ''U.S. News'' rankings of law schools were first released in 1987, W&L Law has had an average ranking of 26th nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-law handbook-Law school rankings 1987-1999|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__1987_1999|publisher=prelawhandbook.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-law handbook-Law school rankings 2000-Present|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__2000_present|publisher=prelawhandbook.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US News Rankings: A Chart of the Past Decade|url=http://www.concurringopinions.com/archives/2006/04/us_news_ranking_1.html|publisher=concurringopinions.com|accessdate=2013-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 2013 Law School Rankings|url=http://www.top-law-schools.com/rankings.html|publisher=top-law-schools.com|accessdate=2013-06-14}}</ref> [[Brian Leiter]] ranked W&L Law's endowment-per-student as 14th in the country, at $214,000 per student, when adjusted for cost-of-living.<ref>{{cite web|title=leiterlawschool.typepad.com|url=http://leiterlawschool.typepad.com/leiter/2006/09/top_20_law_scho.html|publisher=leiterlawschool.typepad.com|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> [[Above the Law (blog)|Above the Law]] ranked W&L Law 22nd nationally in their 2019 Top 50 Law Schools rankings<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2019 ATL Top 50 Law School Rankings|url=https://abovethelaw.com/law-school-rankings/top-law-schools-2019/}}</ref> and, in 2017, 4th nationally in their rankings for the top-rated law schools when measuring alumni satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|title=ATL Law School Rankings: Top Schools By Category|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/06/atl-law-school-rankings-top-schools-by-category/|publisher=abovethelaw.com|accessdate=2015-06-02}}</ref> ''National Jurist'' ranked W&L Law 15th in its list of best law schools for standard of living and 18th in its ranking of the best law libraries.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.nationaljurist.com|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-law-schools-standard-living|accessdate=2011-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=www.nationaljurist.com|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-law-libraries|accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The 2013 edition of ''On Being a Black Lawyer: The Black Student's Guide to Law Schools'', ranked W&L Law 25th in its rankings of the best law schools for black law students.<ref>{{cite web|title=www.onbeingablacklawyer.com|url=http://www.onbeingablacklawyer.com/obabl/schools1/index.html#/14/zoomed|accessdate=2012-10-18}}</ref> In 2013, ''National Jurist'' named W&L's law faculty as the 10th most influential in legal education (the only entire faculty on the list)<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, January 2013|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0113/index.php#/0|accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and 18th in 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, January 2014|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0114/#/14|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> as well as awarding W&L Law's practical training program a B+ grade in its 2014 listing of the best law schools for practical training.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, March 2014|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist0314/#/24|accessdate=2014-03-12}}</ref> ''National Jurist'' also ranked W&L Law as the 5th best value private law school in 2016 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, December 2016|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cypress/nationaljurist_2016fall/#/10|accessdate=2016-12-03}}</ref> A ranking of scholarly impact published in the ''[[University of St. Thomas School of Law|University of St. Thomas Law Journal]]'' ranked the faculty 30th nationally.<ref>{{cite web|title=TaxProf Blog|url=http://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2013/08/the-71.html|accessdate=2013-08-19}}</ref> A 2015 ranking by [[Business Insider]], listed W&L Law as the 17th best law schools in the United States to make connections and get a job.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 best law schools in the US to make connections and get a job|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/best-law-schools-for-networking-in-the-us-2015-6}}</ref> Washington and Lee's ''The Law News'' has been awarded the ABA's award of the finest law school student newspaper four times, including three years in a row, in 1985, 2013, 2014, and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Student Newspaper wins top ABA Award for Second Straight Year|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2014/10/20/wl-law-student-newspaper-wins-top-aba-award-for-second-straight-year/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Student Newspaper Wins Top ABA Award for Third Straight Year|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2015/09/02/wl-law-student-newspaper-wins-top-aba-award-for-third-straight-year/}}</ref> In 2016, ''National Jurist'' included W&L Law on its list of one of the twelve best value private law schools in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Jurist, August 2016|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/content/best-value-law-schools-2016|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==Bar exam results==\nW&L's Virginia [[Admission to the bar in the United States|bar]] passage rate on the July 2017 exam was 86.67% (the state average was 76.43%); W&L had the highest combined average passage rate among Virginia schools for the July 2014 and 2015 exams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barexam.virginia.gov/bar/barresults.html|accessdate=2015-10-30|title=VBBE - Bar Exam - Results}}</ref>  W&L's [[New York (state)|New York]] bar passage rate on the July 2015 exam was 92.86% (the state average for ABA law school graduates was 79%). Nationally, W&L Class of 2014 graduates had a 90% passage rate on bar exams in all states.<ref>{{cite web|title=ABA Required Disclosures|url=http://law.wlu.edu/about-wandl-law/aba-required-disclosures|accessdate=2015-02-10}}</ref> W&L Law was ranked as having the 20th best bar passage rate nationally based on Class of 2015 data.<ref>{{cite web|title=Law schools with highest bar pass rates|url=http://wtop.com/education/2016/05/law-schools-highest-bar-pass-rates/|accessdate=2016-05-31|date=2016-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Post-graduation employment==\nBased on Class of 2015 data, 85% of W&L Law graduates obtained full-time, long term JD-required or preferred jobs within 10 months of graduation. 50% of the 2015 graduates obtained full-time long-term jobs in law firms (including 21% of graduates getting full-time, long term jobs in firms greater than 100 lawyers) and 19% of 2015 graduates obtained clerkships.<ref>{{cite web|title=EMPLOYMENT SUMMARY FOR 2015 GRADUATES|url=http://law2.wlu.edu/admissions/nalp/ABAEmploymentSummary2016.pdf|publisher=law.wlu.edu|accessdate=2016-05-28}}</ref> The large law firms which employed the most W&L Law graduates were [[Hunton & Williams]], [[Alston & Bird]], [[McGuireWoods]], [[K&L Gates]], and [[King & Spalding]].<ref>{{cite web|title=www.abovethelaw.com|url=http://abovethelaw.com/schools/washington-lee-law-school/|publisher=www.abovethelaw.com|accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The School of Law ranked 18th on the 2012 ''U.S. News''' ranking of law schools by recruiters from the top national law firms<ref>{{cite web|title=www.usnews.com|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/articles/2011/03/07/law-firm-recruiters-rank-best-law-schools|publisher=www.usnews.com|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref> and 19th on the 2015 ''U.S News'' ranking of law schools that send the most students to clerk for a [[United States federal judge]] (6.9%).<ref>{{cite web|title=https://www.usnews.com/education/blogs/college-rankings-blog/2014/06/12/grads-of-these-law-schools-get-the-most-judicial-clerkships|publisher=www.usnews.com}}</ref> The ''[[National Law Journal]]'' ranked W&L Law 33rd in its 2015 \"Go-To Law Schools\" list of law schools that send the highest percentage of students to the 250 largest law firms in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://www.nationallawjournal.com/id=1202718517845/The-Top-50-GoTo-Schools?mcode=1202619327776&curindex=0}}</ref>\n\n==Juris Doctor curriculum==\nThe Juris Doctor curriculum at W&L consists three unique and integrated years of full-time study with a mix of traditional [[casebook method]] and practice-oriented courses.\n\n;First-year\n\nIn the 1L year, students take required foundational courses in [[contract law]], [[tort law]], [[Civil procedure in the United States|civil procedure]], [[criminal law]], [[property law]], [[professional responsibility]], [[United States administrative law|administrative law]], and [[international law]]. Additionally, each student is assigned a small section in which one substantive required course also serves as a [[legal writing]] course. This small section consists of approximately 20 students. 1Ls are also assigned to an upper-level student from the Burks Scholar Program who teaches [[legal research]] and [[Bluebook]] methods.\n\n;Second-year\n\nIn the 2L year, students focus on advanced coursework. W&L requires [[evidence law]] and [[United States Constitution|constitutional law]] in the second-year as well as the completion of an upper-level writing requirement. The writing requirement can be satisfied through a seminar course, through an independent writing project, or a note in one of the law journals. All other courses in the 2L year are electives and commonly include [[corporate law]] and [[Taxation in the United States|tax law]] as well as many other classes and seminars. Since establishing the practice-based curriculum, W&L incorporated its experiential curricular offerings, such as practicum courses, into the second-year in addition to casebook-oriented electives.\n\n;Third-year\n\nThe new third-year program, which began in the fall of 2010, replaced further elective advanced coursework based on the casebook method as is the norm in most [[American Bar Association|ABA]] law schools. Instead, the program is meant to  simulate client experiences. The 3L year requires students to exercise professional judgment, work in teams, solve problems, counsel clients, negotiate solutions, serve as advocates and counselors \u2014 the full complement of professional activity that engages practicing lawyers as they apply legal theory and doctrines to the real-world issues of serving clients ethically and honorably within the highest traditions of the profession.\n\nThe Fall semester begins with an immersion course. Students are allowed to choose one of two courses for the two-week immersion. Immersion focuses on either [[litigation]] and [[alternative dispute resolution]] or transactional practice. Each student is then enrolled in practicum courses of their choosing. These courses cover substantive and advanced law but do so through practical methods of drafting paperwork and problem-solving rather than casebook and the [[socratic method]]. Students are also required to take a course in the [[legal profession]] as well as a law-related service requirement. Finally, each student is required to be involved in one of W&L's legal clinics, externship programs, or transnational programs to gain real-client experience. The program is flexible and allows students the ability to tailor their schedule and, if they wish, to take several traditional casebook method courses.\n\n==The Honor System==\nThe [[Honor system|Honor System]] has been run by the student body since 1905 and is derived from Robert E. Lee during his tenure as [[List of Presidents of Washington and Lee University|President]] of the University. Any student found guilty of an Honor Violation by his or her peers is subject to a single penalty: expulsion. The Honor System is defined and administered solely by students, and there is no higher review. A formal review, occasionally including referenda, is held every three years to refine the tenets of the Honor System. Students continue to support the Honor System and its single penalty overwhelmingly, and alumni regularly point to the Honor System as one of the distinctive marks they carry with them from their W&L experience. W&L Law students enjoy several distinct benefits from the Honor System. These include more freedom in exam taking as well as an informal account system at the Brief Stop cafeteria in Sydney Lewis Hall. These are balanced by the strict penalty of a violation of the Honor System.\n\nStudents pledge the following prior to turning in assignments and exams:\n\n\"On my honor, I have neither given nor received any unacknowledged aid on this (exam, test, paper, etc.).\"\n\n==Clinics, journals, moot court, and centers==\n[[File:W&LLawLib.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Wilbur C. Hall Law Library|Wilbur C. Hall Law Library]]\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School houses six clinics:\n* Advanced Administrative Litigation Clinic (Black Lung)\n* Practice Clinic\n* Criminal Justice Clinic\n* Immigrant Rights Clinic\n* Tax Clinic\n* Virginia Capital Case Clearinghouse\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School is home to the following centers:\n* Center for Law and History\n* Frances Lewis Law Center\n* Transnational Law Institute\n* The Law School is also a major partner in the [[Roger Mudd|Mudd Center for Ethics]]\n|}\n\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School offers five moot court programs:\n* Client Counseling Competition\n* The John W. Davis Appellate Advocacy Competition\n* Mock Trial Competition\n* The Robert J. Grey Jr. Negotiations Competition\n* Representation in Mediation Competition\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\nThe Law School is host to three academic journals:\n* ''[[German Law Journal]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.germanlawjournal.com/|title=HOME|website=GERMAN LAW JOURNAL|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref>\n* ''[http://law.wlu.edu/crsj/ Journal of Civil Rights and Social Justice]''\n* ''[[Washington and Lee Law Review]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lawreview.journals.wlu.io/|title=Washington and Lee Law Review|website=lawreview.journals.wlu.io|access-date=2018-02-27}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notable alumni==\nW&L Law has produced many notable graduates in Virginia, and at the national and global level. Included amongst the alumni ranks are two [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court|Justices of the United States Supreme Court]], seven [[List of Presidents of the American Bar Association|Presidents]] of the [[American Bar Association]], two [[Solicitor General of the United States|Solicitors General of the United States]], one major party candidate for [[President of the United States]], [[Cabinet of the United States|Presidential Cabinet]] members, as well as numerous state governors, United States Congressmen, United States Senators, federal and state judges, influential academics, business leaders, and distinguished attorneys. The list below is not exhaustive. The date following the name is the Law School class. Alumni with two dates also attended as undergraduates and the order is alphabetical.\n\n[[File:Newton Baker, Bain bw photo portrait.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Newton D. Baker]], Class of 1894, [[United States Secretary of War]]]]\n[[File:Terry Brooks.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Terry Brooks]], Class of 1969, [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Best Selling Author]]]]\n[[File:John William Davis.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John W. Davis]], Class of 1892, [[United States Solicitor General]]]]\n[[File:John Goode - Brady-Handy.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John Goode]], [[United States Solicitor General]]]]\n[[File:Rep Bob Goodlatte.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Bob Goodlatte]], Class of 1977, Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]]]\n[[File:Joseph Lamar.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[Joseph Rucker Lamar]], Class of 1878, [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court]]]]\n[[File:Marsh, John O 2.jpg|150px|thumb|right|[[John Otho Marsh, Jr.]], Class of 1951, [[United States Secretary of the Army]]]]\n[[File:US Supreme Court Justice Lewis Powell - 1976 official portrait.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.]], Class of 1931, [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court]]]]\n'''Academia'''\n*[[Ronald J. Bacigal]] 1967 \u2014 Professor of law, [[University of Richmond School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronald J. Bacigal|url=http://law.wlu.edu/faculty/profiledetail.asp?id=259|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Charles A. Graves]] 1872 - Professor at W&L Law and at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Charles A. Graves|url=http://law.wlu.edu/faculty/profiledetail.asp?id=356|publisher=Washington and Lee School of Law|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Robert Huntley]] 1950, 1957 - Former Dean of W&L Law, former [[List of Presidents of Washington and Lee University|President of Washington and Lee University]], former President, Chairman, and CEO of [[Best Products]]{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n*[[Robert Shepherd]] 1959, 1961 \u2014 [[Professor emeritus]] of law, [[University of Richmond School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Shepard|url=http://law.richmond.edu/faculty/index.php}}</ref>\n\n'''Arts and entertainment'''\n\n*[[Terry Brooks]] 1969 \u2014  [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times bestselling author]] of [[Fantasy literature|fantasy fiction]] and creator of the [[Shannara]] fantasy series<ref>{{cite web|title=Terry Brooks|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/412/000026334/|publisher=NNDB Soylent Communications|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[David Brown (radio host)|David Brown]] 2000 - Former host of the ''[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]'' radio program, current anchor of the Texas Standard\n*[[Gay Elmore]] - Two time [[Southern Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year]]\n\n'''Business'''\n*[[Sydney Lewis]] 1940, 1943 - Prominent Virginia businessman, art collector, and founder of [[Best Products]], recipient with his wife, Frances, in 1987, of the National Medal of the Arts <ref>{{cite web|title=National Medal of the Arts|url=http://arts.gov/honors/medals/mr-and-mrs-sydney-lewis|publisher=National Endowment for the Arts|accessdate=27 March 2015|date=2013-04-24}}</ref>\n*[[Gordon P. Robertson]] - CEO of the [[Christian Broadcasting Network]]\n\n'''Government and politics'''\n\n*[[Samuel B. Avis]] - [[United States Congressman]] from [[West Virginia]] from 1913 to 1915\n*[[Robert D. Bailey, Jr.]] - [[West Virginia Secretary of State]] from 1965 to 1969\n*[[Newton D. Baker]] 1894 \u2014 [[Secretary of War]] under President [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[List of mayors of Cleveland|Mayor of Cleveland, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Newton D. Baker|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/535/000113196/|publisher=NNDB Soylent Communications|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> and named partner at [[BakerHostetler]]\n*[[Franklin Brockson]] - United States Congressman from [[Delaware]] from 1913 to 1915\n*[[Clarence J. Brown]] 1915 - President of [[Brown Publishing Company]] and US Congressman from Ohio from 1939 to 1965\n*[[Nathan P. Bryan]] 1895 - US Senator from the State of Florida, Judge on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Nathan P. Bryan|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000992|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[William James Bryan]] 1899 - US Senator from Florida<ref>{{cite web|title=William James Bryan|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B000994|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Bruce L. Castor, Jr.]] 1986 \u2014 Attorney General (interim) and Solicitor General of Pennsylvania; District Attorney, [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]] (2000\u20132008); Commissioner, Montgomery County, Pennsylvania (2008-2016 ); President Pennsylvania District Attorneys' Association<ref>{{cite web|title=Bruce L. Castor, Jr.|url=http://www2.montcopa.org/montco/cwp/view,a,3,q,87046.asp|publisher=County of Montgomery, PA|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Edward Cooper (congressman)|Edward Cooper]] - US Congressman from West Virginia from 1915 to 1919\n*[[Spencer Cox (politician)|Spencer Cox]] 2001 - [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Spencer Cox|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2013/10/09/wl-law-alum-named-utahs-lieutenant-governor/|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n*[[William Fadjo Cravens]] - US Congressman from Arkansas\n*[[John J. Davis (congressman)|John J. Davis]] 1856 - [[United States Representative]] from [[West Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John J. Davis|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000119|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[John W. Davis]] 1895, 1892 \u2014 1924 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[United States President]]; Ambassador to [[United Kingdom|Britain]]; [[United States Solicitor General|Solicitor General]]; argued more cases before the Supreme Court than anyone else in the twentieth century; [[American Bar Association]] President; first President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]; and named partner at [[Davis Polk & Wardwell]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John W. Davis|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000121|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Joe Donnelly]] 1981- United States Senator from [[Indiana]]<ref>{{cite web|title=W&L Law Alums Win Elections in Virginia, Indiana|url=http://news.blogs.wlu.edu/2012/11/07/wl-law-alums-win-elections-in-virginia-indiana/|publisher=Washington and Lee University|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[John P. Fishwick, Jr.]], former [[United States Attorney]] for the [[Western District of Virginia]]. Attorney in private practice in [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n*[[Vance A. Funk, III]] 1968 - [[Mayor]] of [[Newark, Delaware]]\n*[[John Goode]] - 3rd [[Solicitor General of the United States]] and [[United States Congressman]] from Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=John Goode|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000277|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Bob Goodlatte]] 1977 - United States Congressman from Virginia and Chair of the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Bob Goodlatte|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=g000289|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[R. Booth Goodwin]] 1996 - [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for t