 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d750 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalGold |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d750 m mixed freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|4\u00d750 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver |2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 50 metre medley relay|4\u00d750 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2018 Tokyo]] | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 2018 Tokyo | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}} \n{{MedalSilver | 2018 Tokyo | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]}} \n{{MedalSilver | 2018 Tokyo | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2018 Tokyo | [[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FINA World Junior Swimming Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 FINA World Junior Swimming Championships|2013 Dubai]] | 100 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Dubai | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Dubai | 4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2013 Dubai | 50&nbsp;m freestyle}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2013 Dubai | 4\u00d7200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2013 Dubai | 4\u00d7100 m mixed medley}}\n}}\n'''Caeleb Remel Dressel''' (born August 16, 1996) is an American [[Freestyle swimming|freestyle]] and [[butterfly stroke|butterfly]] swimmer who specializes in the sprint events. He currently represents the Cali Condors Swim Club which is part of the [[International Swimming League]]. He won seven gold medals at the [[2017 World Aquatics Championships]] in Budapest and a record eight medals, including six gold, at the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]] in Gwangju.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/caeleb-dressels-8-medals-set-single-meet-record-at-worlds/ |title=Caeleb Dressel's eight medals set single-meet record at worlds |first1=Torrey |last1=Hart |date=July 28, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] |accessdate=July 28, 2019}}</ref> Dressel is a two-time Olympic gold medalist and currently holds the [[List of world records in swimming|world record]] in the 100 meter butterfly ([[long course]]).\n\nDressel holds the [[List of United States records in swimming|American records]] in 50-meter and 100-meter freestyle and in 50-meter and 100-meter butterfly (all long course). He also holds the short course records in 50-yard and 100-yard freestyle events, the 100-yard butterfly, and the 200-yard individual medley, and formerly in the 100-yard breaststroke.\n\n==Early life==\nDressel was born on August 16, 1996 in [[Green Cove Springs, Florida]], the son of Christina and Michael Dressel. He is the third of four children; his three siblings, Tyler, Kaitlyn, and Sherridon are all competitive swimmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailydsports.com/caeleb-dressel/ |title=Caeleb Dressel is the greatest college swimmer of all time |date=November 19, 2018 |work=Daily Sports }}</ref>\n\nDressel attended Clay High School in Green Cove Springs, Florida, but trained with the [[Bolles School]] Sharks in [[Jacksonville]]. He was a collegiate swimmer at the [[University of Florida]] starting in 2014, and graduated in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/bio/caeleb-dressel/ |title=Caeleb Dressel|work=SwimSwam }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n==International Swimming League==\nIn 2019 he was a member of the inaugural [[International Swimming League]] representing the Cali Condors, who finished third place in the final match in Las Vegas, Nevada in December. Dressel won the MVP in all 3 matches he participated in as well as winning the skins race each time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/2019-isl-match-2-in-naples-dressel-mvp-but-ens-leads-day-2-points-totals/ |title=2019 isl match 2 in naples dressel mvp but ens leads day 2 points totals |first1=Anne |last1=Lepesant |date=October 13, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] |accessdate=October 13, 2019 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/sarah-sjostrom-wins-season-mvp-50000-bonus-prize-in-isl-finale/ |title=sarah sjostrom wins season mvp 50000 bonus prize in isl finale |first1=Braden |last1=Keith |date=December 21, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] |accessdate=December 21, 2019 }} </ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/dressel-wins-second-mvp-award-of-isl-season-in-cali-loss/ |title=Dressel wins second MVP award of isl season in cali loss |first1=Jared |last1=Anderson |date=November 18, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] }} </ref>\n\n===2012===\nAt the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|2012 United States Olympic Trials]], Dressel was the youngest male swimmer at 15 and placed 145th in the 50-meter freestyle and tied for 152nd in the 100-meter freestyle.\n\n===2013===\nAt the [[2013 FINA World Junior Swimming Championships]] in Dubai, Dressel won six medals, including a gold medal in the 100 meter freestyle, breaking the [[FINA World Junior Swimming Championships#Championships records|Championships record]].\n\nAt the 2013 Speedo Winter Junior National Championships (the [[USA Swimming]] sanctioned national championship meet for 18 and under swimmers), Dressel became the youngest swimmer in history to break the 19 second barrier in the 50 yard freestyle, swimming an 18.94 to lead off his club team's relay.<ref name=\"SWM2\">{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/hes-done-caeleb-dressel-goes-19-seconds-just-17-years-old/ |title=HE\u2019S DONE IT: CAELEB DRESSEL GOES UNDER 19 SECONDS AT JUST 17 YEARS OLD |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nDuring his freshman year at the [[University of Florida]], he won the 2015 [[NCAA]] title in the 50 yard freestyle.<ref name=\"SWM\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/video-interview-caeleb-dressel-storms-to-third-in-the-world/ |title=Video Interview: Caeleb Dressel Storms to Third in the World |magazine=[[Swimming World]] |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> At the senior [[United States Swimming National Championships|2015 National Championships]] (long course) in San Antonio, he won two individual titles, in the 50 meter and the 100 meter freestyle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020B00000002FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |title=Men's 50 meter freestyle final results |publisher=Omega Timing |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010F020B00000102FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |title=Men's 100 meter freestyle final results |publisher=Omega Timing |accessdate=August 22, 2015}}</ref> His winning time of 21.53 in the 50 meter freestyle ranked 4th in the world for 2015.<ref name=\"SWM\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/caaleb-dressel-takes-gold-in-50-free-final-at-usa-nationals/ |title=Caeleb Dressel Takes Gold In 50 Free Final At USA Nationals |date=August 8, 2015 |magazine=[[Swimming World]] |access-date=November 5, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swimvortex.com/bruno-fratus-leads-the-speed-stakes-with-21-37-relay-opener-at-brazil-nationals/ |title=Bruno Fratus Leads The Speed Stakes With 21.37 Relay Opener At Brazil Nationals |first1=Craig |last1=Lord |date=December 17, 2015 |publisher=Swimvortex |access-date=December 17, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608145657/http://www.swimvortex.com/bruno-fratus-leads-the-speed-stakes-with-21-37-relay-opener-at-brazil-nationals/ |archive-date=June 8, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2016===\n[[File:Michael Phelps and Caeleb Dressel Rio 2016.jpg|thumbnail|[[Michael Phelps]] and Dressel (right) after winning the 4 \u00d7 100 m freestyle relay at the 2016 Olympics.]]\nAt the [[2016 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships|2016 Men's NCAA Division I Championships]], he broke the [[List of United States records in swimming|American and US Open records]] in the 50-yard freestyle with a time of 18.20<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/caeleb-dressel-swims-18-20-in-ncaa-50-free-final-breaks-all-records/ |title=Caeleb Dressel swims 18.20 in NCAA 50 free final, breaks all records |first1=Braden |last1=Keith |date=March 24, 2016 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=March 26, 2016 }}</ref> and the 100-yard freestyle with 40.46.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/caeleb-dressel-unleashes-4046-ncaa-american-record-100-free/ |title=(Race Video) Caeleb Dressel Unleashes 40.46 NCAA, American Record to Win 100 Free |date=March 26, 2016 |magazine=[[Swimming World]] |access-date=March 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n====2016 Summer Olympics====\nAt the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio de Janeiro, Dressel won his first gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]]. In the final, he swam the lead-off leg in 48.10 (the second-fastest opening leg in the field), and was followed by teammates [[Michael Phelps]], [[Ryan Held]], and [[Nathan Adrian]]. The American team recorded a time of 3:09.92.\n\nIn the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]], Dressel finished sixth in the final with a time of 48.02.\n\nDressel also swam in the heats of the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-meter medley relay]], and earned his second gold medal when the USA finished first in the finals. He recorded a freestyle split of 47.74 in the heats.\n\n===2017===\nAt the [[2017 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships|2017 NCAA Division I Championships]], he broke the American and US Open records in the 100-yard butterfly and the 100-yard freestyle with times of 43.58<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/dressel-upsets-schooling-sets-new-ncaa-record-43-58/ |title=Dressel Upsets Schooling; Sets New NCAA Record in 43.58 |first1=Lauren |last1=Neidigh |date=March 24, 2017 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=March 25, 2017 }}</ref> and 40.00,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/caeleb-dressel-annihilates-american-record-40-00-100-free/|title=Caeleb Dressel Annihilates American Record with 40.00 100 Free |first1=Lauren |last1=Neidigh |date=March 25, 2017 |publisher=Swimswam |access-date=March 25, 2017 }}</ref> respectively. He also tied his 50 freestyle record with an 18.20, the same as the preceding year.\n\n====2017 World Championships====\n{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]| 21.15 (NR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]| 47.17 (NR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]]| 49.86 }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] | 3:10.06}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]] | 3:27.91 }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle]]| 3:19.60 (WR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]| 3:38.56 (WR)}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\nAt the [[2017 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Budapest]], Hungary, Dressel won seven gold medals and set numerous American records. Dressel was named the male swimmer of the meet. He also became the second swimmer to win seven gold medals at a single World Championships, after [[Michael Phelps]] in 2007.\n\nOn the first day of competition, July 23, Dressel set the [[List of United States records in swimming|American record]] in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre butterfly|50 meter butterfly]] with a time of 22.76, topping the semifinals. Later that evening in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]], Dressel set the American record in the 100 meter freestyle with a time of 47.26 in the leadoff leg. Combined with [[Townley Haas]], [[Blake Pieroni]], and [[Nathan Adrian]], the American team won gold with a time of 3:10.06, earning him his first gold of the Championships.\n\nOn day two, Dressel finished fourth in the 50 meter butterfly final with a time of 22.89, missing a medal by 0.05 seconds. On day four, Dressel took part in the 4\u00d7100 meter mixed medley relay, swimming the butterfly leg and splitting a 49.92. Along with teammates [[Matt Grevers]], [[Lilly King]], and [[Simone Manuel]], the American team won gold in a new world record time of 3:38.56.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/2017-worlds-mixed-medley-relay-record-goes-finals/|title=2017 Worlds: Mixed Medley Relay Record Goes Down Again in Finals|date=2017-07-26|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2017-07-26}}</ref> That time broke the record set earlier in the day by [[Ryan Murphy (swimmer)|Ryan Murphy]], [[Kevin Cordes]], [[Kelsi Worrell]], and [[Mallory Comerford]]. On day five, Dressel re-set the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]] American record with a 47.17 in the 100 meter freestyle final, en route to winning gold by a margin of 0.70 seconds over silver medalist and teammate Nathan Adrian.\n\nOn day seven, Dressel became the first swimmer ever to win three gold medals on a single day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jul/29/caeleb-dressel-three-golds-worlds-katie-ledecky |title=Caeleb Dressel becomes first ever to win three gold medals in one night at worlds |date=July 29, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=July 30, 2017 }}</ref> He won the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 meter freestyle]] in 21.15, a new [[List of textile best times in swimming|world textile best time]]. Half an hour later he won the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 meter butterfly]] in 49.86, again a new world textile best and 0.04 seconds above the world record held by [[Michael Phelps]]. The third gold medal came in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 meter mixed freestyle relay]], where he led off in 47.22. Dressel and teammates Adrian, Comerford, and Manuel broke the world record for this relay with a time of 3:19.60.\n\nOn the eighth and last day of competition, Dressel won his 7th gold in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-meter medley relay]]. Swimming the butterfly leg, Dressel recorded a time of 49.76 and the American team of [[Matt Grevers]], [[Kevin Cordes]], and [[Nathan Adrian]] won with a time of 3:27.91.\n\n===2018===\n[[File:Caeleb Dressel during 100 fly (42052333224).jpg|thumb|Dressel in the 100 fly]]\nAt the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships]], Dressel won all three of his individual races, and won his first relay national title.\n\nOn day 2 of the competition, March 22, 2018, Dressel broke the American and US Open records in the 50 yard freestyle thrice. He first swam an 18.11 in the individual preliminaries race in the morning session. He later improved upon that record in the evening leading off The [[University of Florida]]'s national championship winning relay with a 17.81 split, and finalized his record with a 17.63 in the 50 yard freestyle final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/2018-mens-ncaa-championships-day-2-finals-live-recap/|title=2018 MEN\u2019S NCAA CHAMPIONSHIPS: DAY 2 FINALS LIVE RECAP|date=2018-03-23|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-06-01}}</ref> The next day, he broke the American and US open records in the 100 yard butterfly, swimming a 42.80.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/2018-m-ncaas-dressel-42/|title=2018 M. NCAAS: DRESSEL CRACKS 43 WITH 42.80 100 FLY|date=2018-03-23|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-06-01}}</ref> On the final day of competition, Dressel won the 100 yard freestyle by more than a second in a time of 39.90, completing his sweep of individual events for a second time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/2018-mens-ncaa-championships-day-4-finals-live-recap/|title=2018 MEN\u2019S NCAA CHAMPIONSHIPS: DAY 4 FINALS LIVE RECAP|date=2018-03-24|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-06-01}}</ref> This secured him CSCAA Swimmer of the Meet honors for the third year in a row, as he became the first swimmer ever to break the 18 second 50 free barrier, the 40 second 100 free barrier, and the 43 second 100 fly barrier in the history of yards swimming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://swimswam.com/barrier-breaking-dressel-earns-cscaas-swimmer-of-year-award-for-2018/|title=BARRIER-BREAKING DRESSEL EARNS CSCAA\u2019S SWIMMER OF YEAR AWARD FOR 2018|date=2018-03-24|work=SwimSwam|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2018, Dressel signed with [[Speedo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/caeleb-dressel-officially-signs-deal-with-speedo/|title=Caeleb Dressel Officially Signs Deal With Speedo |work=Swimming World |first=Andy |last=Ross|date= July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n====2019 World Championships====\n{{MedalTableTop|name=no|header=[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]| 21.04 (NR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]| 46.96 (NR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre butterfly|50 m butterfly]]| 22.35 (AM)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100 m butterfly]]| 49.50 (sf) (WR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] | 3:09.06 (CR)}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed freestyle]]| 3:19.40 (WR)}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]] | 3:28.45}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]| 3:39.10}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\nAt the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]] held in [[Gwangju]], South Korea, he first won a gold as part of the team in [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|Men's 4 \u00d7 100 m freestyle relay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/caeleb-dressel-nathan-adrian-gwangju/ |title=Caeleb Dressel hails Nathan Adrian as Team USA wins relay gold at FINA World Championships|first= Andrew |last=Binner|date=21 July 2019 |work=Olympic Channel }}</ref> He then won gold in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre butterfly|50m butterfly]], an event he failed to win in 2017. He is the first American man to win that event, and he set a new national and championship record time of 22.35 second for the event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teamusa.org/News/2019/July/22/With-50-Meter-Butterfly-World-Title-Caeleb-Dressel-Claims-The-One-That-Got-Away-In-17 |title=With 50-Meter Butterfly World Title, Caeleb Dressel Claims The One That Got Away In \u201817 |first= Karen |last= Price |date= July 22, 2019 |work=Team USA }}</ref> This is followed by a national record and the third fastest time in history (46.96) in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100m freestyle]].<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nbcsports.com/video/2019-world-swimming-championships-caeleb-dressel-repeats-100m-freestyle |title=Dressel repeats as 100m freestyle world champion|work=NBC Sports |date=25 July 2019 }}</ref>It is important to note that he did so in a textile suit, which is substantially less buoyant than the full body suit used to set the record.\n\nIn the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly|100m butterfly]] event, Dressel broke Michael Phelps' ten-year-old record by 0.32 second in the semi-final, setting a new world record time of 49.50 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/49127897 |title=World Aquatics Championships: Caeleb Dressel breaks Michael Phelps' 10-year-old world record |work=BBC |date=July 26, 2019 }}</ref> He won gold in the final the following day. That same day within two hours, Dressel won two further golds &ndash; in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50m freestyle]] in a Championships record time, and as part of the team in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed freestyle relay|mixed 4x100-meter freestyle relay]], which was won in a world record time of 3 minutes, 19.40 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/general/news/american-swimmer-caeleb-dressel-wins-three-titles-in-one-night-at-world-championships-puts-gold-medal-count-at-six/ |title=American swimmer Caeleb Dressel wins three titles in one night at World Championships, puts gold medal count at six |first= Shanna |last=McCarriston|date=27 July 2019 |work=CBS Sports }}</ref>  This is a repeat of his achievement in Hungary in 2017, and it is also the first time anyone has won three gold medals in a single day at the Championships twice.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jul/27/katie-ledecky-caeleb-dressel-swimming-worlds |title='It was not easy': Caeleb Dressel wins three titles in one night at swim worlds |agency=Associated Press |work=The Guardian |date=27 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the final day of the Championships, Dressel helped United States win a silver in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/duncan-scott-splits-46-1-to-overhaul-adrian-as-great-britain-take-gold-in-4x100-medley-relay-russia-third/ |title=Scott Splits 46.14 To Overhaul Adrian As Great Britain Take Gold in 4\u00d7100 Medley Relay: Russia Third |first=Liz |last= Byrnes|date=28 July 2019|work=Swimming World }}</ref> The medal is the eighth that Dressel won at the Championships, and the most anyone has won at a single Championships.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-07-28/caleb-dressel-eight-medals-world-swimming-championships |title=U.S swimmer Caeleb Dressel wins record eighth medal at world championships |agency= Associated Press|date=July 28, 2019|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> He was named FINA male swimmer of the meet, which he also won in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/caeleb-dressel-sarah-sjostrom-crowned-swimmers-of-the-meet-at-fina-world-swimming-championships/|title=Caeleb Dressel, Sarah Sjostrom Crowned Swimmers of the Meet at FINA World Swimming Championships | first= Andy |last= Ross|date=July 28, 2019|work=Swimming World}}</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\n{{updated|December 24, 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Long course'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! Event\n! Time\n! Meet\n! Date\n! {{nowrap|Note(s)}}\n|-\n| 50&nbsp;m freestyle\n| '''21.04'''\n|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|2019 World Championships]]\n|July 27, 2019\n|'''[[List of United States records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|-\n| 100&nbsp;m freestyle\n| '''46.96'''\n|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|2019 World Championships]]\n| July 25, 2019\n|'''[[List of United States records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|-\n| 200&nbsp;m freestyle\n| '''1:47.31'''\n|2019 TYR Pro Swim Series\n| April 11, 2019\n|\n|-\n| 50&nbsp;m butterfly\n| '''22.35'''\n|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre butterfly|2019 World Championships]]\n| July 22, 2019\n|'''[[List of Americas records in swimming|AM]]'''\n|-\n| 100&nbsp;m butterfly\n| '''49.50'''\n|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Championships]]\n|July 26, 2019\n|'''[[List of world records in swimming|WR]]'''\n|-\n| 200&nbsp;m individual medley\n| '''2:01.72'''\n|2019 TYR Pro Swim Series\n| April 13, 2019\n|\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Short course'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! Event\n! Time\n! Meet\n! Date\n! {{nowrap|Note(s)}}\n|-\n|50 m freestyle\n|'''20.24'''\n|[[2019 International Swimming League|International Swimming League]]\n|December 20, 2019\n|'''[[List of world records in swimming|WR]]'''\n|-\n|100 m freestyle\n|'''45.22'''\n|[[2019 International Swimming League|International Swimming League]]\n|December 21, 2019\n|'''[[List of United States records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|-\n|50 m butterfly\n|'''22.06'''\n|[[2019 International Swimming League|International Swimming League]]\n|December 21, 2019\n|'''[[List of United States records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|-\n|100 m butterfly\n|'''48.71'''\n|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 World Championships]]\n|December 13, 2018\n|\n|}\n\n* Dressel swam one of the fastest relay splits in history in the mixed 4x50 medley relay in 20.09. The only sub-20 splits ever were done in the same relay, when [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rick Bousquet]] (19.87) and [[Amaury Leveaux]] (19.93) did so for France at the 2008 European Championships.<ref>https://swimswam.com/watch-dressel-make-up-2-second-deficit-with-20-0-anchor/</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Short course yards'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! Event\n! Time\n! Meet\n! Date\n! {{nowrap|Note(s)}}\n|-\n|50 yd freestyle\t\n|'''17.63'''\t\n|[[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships|2018 NCAA Championships]]\n|March 22, 2018\t\n|'''[[List of United States records in swimming|NR]]'''\n|-\n|100 yd freestyle\t\n|'''39.90'''\t\n|[[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships|2018 NCAA Championships]]\t\n|March 24, 2018\t\n|NR\n|-\n|100 yd breaststroke\t\n|'''50.03'''\n|2018 SEC Swimming & Diving Championships\n|February 17, 2018\t\n|Former NR\n|-\n|100 yd butterfly\t\n|'''42.80'''\t\n|[[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Swimming and Diving Championships|2018 NCAA Championships]]\t\n|March 23, 2018\t\n|NR\n|-\n|200 yd individual medley \n|'''1:38.13'''\t\n|2018 SEC Swimming & Diving Championships\n|February 15, 2018\t\n|NR\n|}\n\n==World Records==\n\n===Long Course Meters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!No.\n!Event\n!Time\n!Meet\n!Date\n|-\n|1\n|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m mixed medley relay\n|'''3:38.56'''\n|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Championships]]\n|{{dts|2017|Jul|27|format=mdy}}\n|-\n|2\n|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m mixed freestyle relay\n|'''3:19.60'''\n|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Championships]]\n|{{dts|2017|Jul|29|format=mdy}}\n|-\n|3\n|100&nbsp;m butterfly\n|'''49.50''' (sf)\n|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Championships]]\n|{{dts|2019|Jul|26|format=mdy}}\n|-\n|4\n|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m mixed freestyle relay (2)\n|'''3:19.40'''\n|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 World Championships]]\